{"title_page": "Nabitan", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 421099167\n| IUPAC_name = 5,5-Dimethyl-8-(3-methyloctan-2-yl)-2-(prop-2-yn-1-yl)-1,3,4,5-tetrahydro-2''H''-[1]benzopyrano[4,3-''c'']pyridin-10-yl 4-(piperidin-1-yl)butanoate\n| image = Nabitan.svg\n| width = 180\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 66556-74-9\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = JO7BOR6B3O\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| PubChem = 39503\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 36117\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=35 | H=52 | N=2 | O=3 \n| molecular_weight = 548.799 g/mol\n| smiles = O=C(Oc2cc(cc1OC(C\\3=C(/c12)CN(CC/3)CC#C)(C)C)C(C)C(C)CCCCC)CCCN4CCCCC4\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C35H52N2O3/c1-7-9-11-15-26(3)27(4)28-23-31(39-33(38)16-14-21-36-19-12-10-13-20-36)34-29-25-37(18-8-2)22-17-30(29)35(5,6)40-32(34)24-28/h2,23-24,26-27H,7,9-22,25H2,1,3-6H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = MCVPMHDADNVRKF-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n'''Nabitan''' ('''Nabutam''', '''Benzopyranoperidine''', '''SP-106''', '''Abbott 40656''') is a [[Chemical synthesis|synthetic]] [[cannabinoid]] [[Analog (chemistry)|analog]] of [[dronabinol]] (Marinol).<ref>Razdan RK. The Total Synthesis of Cannabinoids. Wiley-Interscience 1980</ref> It exhibits [[antiemetic]] and [[analgesic]] effects, most likely by binding to and activating the CB<sub>1</sub> and CB<sub>2</sub> [[cannabinoid receptor]]s, and reduced [[intraocular pressure]] in animal tests, making it potentially useful in the treatment of [[glaucoma]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Razdan RK, Howes JF | title = Drugs related to tetrahydrocannabinol | journal = Medicinal Research Reviews | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 119\u201346 | pmid = 6134882 }}</ref>\n\nNabitan has the advantage of being water-soluble, unlike most cannabinoid derivatives, and was researched for potential use as an analgesic or [[sedative]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Archer RA | title = The cannabinoids: therapeutic potentials | journal = Annual Reports in Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 9 | pages = 253\u20139 | pmid = 12307093 }}</ref> although it was never developed for clinical use and is not currently used in medicine, as [[dronabinol]] or [[nabilone]] were felt to be more useful. However it is sometimes used in research into the potential therapeutic applications of cannabinoids. \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cannabinoids}}\n{{Hallucinogens}}\n{{Cannabinoidergics}}\n\n[[Category:Alkyne derivatives]]\n[[Category:Butyrates]]\n[[Category:Cannabinoids]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen heterocycles]]\n[[Category:Oxygen heterocycles]]\n[[Category:Heterocyclic compounds (3 rings)]]\n[[Category:Piperidines]]\n\n{{cannabinoid-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| verifiedrevid = 421099167\n| IUPAC_name = 5,5-Dimethyl-8-(3-methyloctan-2-yl)-2-(prop-2-yn-1-yl)-1,3,4,5-tetrahydro-2''H''-[1]benzopyrano[4,3-''c'']pyridin-10-yl 4-(piperidin-1-yl)butanoate\n| image = Nabitan.svg\n| width = 180\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename =  \n| legal_status =  \n| routes_of_administration =  \n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| metabolism =  \n| elimination_half-life =  \n| excretion =  \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CAS_number = 66556-74-9\n| ATC_prefix = none\n| PubChem = 39503\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 36117\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=35 | H=52 | N=2 | O=3 \n| molecular_weight = 548.799 g/mol\n| smiles = O=C(Oc2cc(cc1OC(C\\3=C(/c12)CN(CC/3)CC#C)(C)C)C(C)C(C)CCCCC)CCCN4CCCCC4\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C35H52N2O3/c1-7-9-11-15-26(3)27(4)28-23-31(39-33(38)16-14-21-36-19-12-10-13-20-36)34-29-25-37(18-8-2)22-17-30(29)35(5,6)40-32(34)24-28/h2,23-24,26-27H,7,9-22,25H2,1,3-6H3\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = MCVPMHDADNVRKF-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n'''Nabitan''' ('''Nabutam''', '''Benzopyranoperidine''', '''SP-106''', '''Abbott 40656''') is a [[Chemical synthesis|synthetic]] [[cannabinoid]] [[Analog (chemistry)|analog]] of [[dronabinol]] (Marinol).<ref>Razdan RK. The Total Synthesis of Cannabinoids. Wiley-Interscience 1980</ref> It exhibits [[antiemetic]] and [[analgesic]] effects, most likely by binding to and activating the CB<sub>1</sub> and CB<sub>2</sub> [[cannabinoid receptor]]s, and reduced [[intraocular pressure]] in animal tests, making it potentially useful in the treatment of [[glaucoma]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Razdan RK, Howes JF | title = Drugs related to tetrahydrocannabinol | journal = Medicinal Research Reviews | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 119\u201346 | pmid = 6134882 }}</ref>\n\nNabitan has the advantage of being water-soluble, unlike most cannabinoid derivatives, and was researched for potential use as an analgesic or [[sedative]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Archer RA | title = The cannabinoids: therapeutic potentials | journal = Annual Reports in Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 9 | pages = 253\u20139 | pmid = 12307093 }}</ref> although it was never developed for clinical use and is not currently used in medicine, as [[dronabinol]] or [[nabilone]] were felt to be more useful. However it is sometimes used in research into the potential therapeutic applications of cannabinoids. \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cannabinoids}}\n{{Hallucinogens}}\n{{Cannabinoidergics}}\n\n[[Category:Alkyne derivatives]]\n[[Category:Butyrates]]\n[[Category:Cannabinoids]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen heterocycles]]\n[[Category:Oxygen heterocycles]]\n[[Category:Heterocyclic compounds (3 rings)]]\n[[Category:Piperidines]]\n\n{{cannabinoid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nabitan"}
{"title_page": "Red junglefowl", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of bird; wild origin of the domesticated chicken}}\n{{Redirect|Gallus gallus|other subspecies|Chicken}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Red junglefowl\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22679199/92806965 |title=''Gallus gallus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Red Junglefowl - Thailand.jpg\n| image_alt = Male red junglefowl walking across forest floor\n| genus = Gallus\n| species = gallus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Gallus gallus map.jpg\n| range_map_alt = World map showing range confined to Southeast Asia\n| range_map_caption = Red junglefowl range\n| synonyms = ''Phasianus gallus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''red junglefowl''' (''Gallus gallus'') is a [[tropical]] bird in the family [[Phasianidae]]. It ranges across much of [[Southeast Asia]] and parts of [[South Asia]]. Red junglefowl are the primary progenitor of the domestic [[chicken]] (''Gallus gallus domesticus''), but the [[grey junglefowl]], [[Sri Lankan junglefowl]] and [[green junglefowl]] have also contributed genetic materials to the gene pool of the domestic chicken.<ref name=Lawal>{{ cite journal | last1=Lawal | first1=RA. | display-authors=etal  | year=2020 | title=The wild species genome ancestry of domestic chickens | journal=BMC Biology | volume=18 | issue=13 | pages=13 | doi=10.1186/s12915-020-0738-1 | doi-access=free | pmid=32050971 }}</ref><ref name=\"Eriksson\">{{Citation |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1000010.eor |pmid=18454198 |author1=Eriksson, Jonas |author2=Larson, Greger |author3=Gunnarsson, Ulrika |author4=Bed'hom, Bertrand |author5=Tixier-Boichard, Michele |author6=Str\u00f6mstedt, Lina |author7=Wright, Dominic |author8=Jungerius, Annemieke |author9=Vereijken, Addie |author10=Randi, Ettore |author11=Jensen, Per |author12=Andersson, Leif |title=Identification of the Yellow Skin Gene Reveals a Hybrid Origin of the Domestic Chicken |publisher=PLoS Genet |pages=e10 |volume=preprint |date=23 January 2008 |journal=PLoS Genetics |displayauthors=8 |issue=2008  |doi-access=free }}</ref> \n\nEvidence from the molecular level derived from whole-genome sequencing revealed that chicken was domesticated from red junglefowl about 8,000 years ago<ref name = Lawal />, with this domestication event involving multiple maternal origins.<ref name = Lawal /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{ cite journal | last1=Liu | first1=Y-P. | display-authors=etal  | year=2006 | title=Multiple Maternal Origins of Chickens: Out of the Asian Jungles | journal=Mol Phylogenet Evol | volume=38 | issue=1 | pages=12\u20139 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2005.09.014 | doi-access=free | pmid=16275023 }}</ref> Since then, their domestic form has spread around the world and is kept globally as a source of meat and eggs.<ref name=\"Storey\" />\n\n== Taxonomy and systematics ==\n{{main article|Junglefowl}}\nNumerous wild and domestic subspecies of ''Gallus gallus'' exist, including:\n* ''G. g. gallus'' \u2013 from [[Southeast Asia]]\n* ''G. g. bankiva'' \u2013 from [[Java]]\n* ''G. g. jabouillei'' \u2013 from [[Vietnam]]\n* ''G. g. murghi'' \u2013 from [[India]] and [[Bangladesh]]\n* ''G. g. spadiceus'' \u2013 from [[Burma]]\n* ''[[Chicken|G. g. domesticus]]'' \u2013 domestic chicken\n{{Cladogram\n|caption=[[Cladogram]] showing the species in the genus ''[[Gallus (genus)|Gallus]]''.<ref name = Lawal /><ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Tiley | first1=G.P. | last2=Pandey | first2=A. | last3=Kimball | first3=R.T. | last4=Braun | first4=E.L. | last5=Burleigh | first5=J.G. | year=2020| title=Whole genome phylogeny of ''Gallus'': introgression and data\u2011type effects | journal=Avian Research | volume=11 | issue=7 | doi=10.1186/s40657-020-00194-w | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n|align=right\n|cladogram={{Cladex| style=font-size:80%;line-height:75%;width:320px;\n|label1=''Gallus''&nbsp; \n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Grey junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus sonneratii''\n         |2=[[Sri Lanka junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus lafayettii''\n         }}\n      |2=[[Red junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus gallus''\n      }}\n    |2=[[Green junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus varius''\n    }}\n}}\n}}\n\n== Description ==\nThe [[nominate race]] of red junglefowl has a mix of feather colours, with orange, brown, red, gold, grey, white, olive and even metallic green plumage. The tail of the male roosters can grow up to {{Convert|28|cm|in|abbr=}}, and the whole bird may be as long as {{Convert|70|cm|in|abbr=}}. There are 14 tail feathers. A moult in June changes the bird's plumage to an eclipse pattern, which lasts through October. The male eclipse pattern includes a black feather in the middle of the back and small red-orange plumes spread across the body. Female eclipse plumage is generally indistinguishable from the plumage at other seasons, but the moulting schedule is the same as that of males.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Gallus_gallus/|title=Gallus gallus (red junglefowl)|last=Gautier|first=Zoe|website=Animal Diversity Web|language=en|access-date=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nCompared to the more familiar domestic chicken, the red junglefowl has a much smaller body mass (around 2\u00bc lbs (1 kg) in females and 3\u00bc lbs (1.5kg) in males) and is brighter in coloration.<ref name=\":0\" /> Junglefowl are also behaviourally different from domestic chickens, being naturally very shy of humans compared to the much tamer domesticated subspecies.\n\n===Sexual dimorphism===\nMale junglefowl are significantly larger than females and have brightly coloured decorative feathers. The male's tail is composed of long, arching feathers that initially look black, but shimmer with blue, purple, and green in direct light. He also has long, golden hackle feathers on his neck and on his back. The female's [[plumage]] is typical of this family of birds in being [[crypsis|cryptic]] and [[adaptation|adapted]] for [[camouflage]]. She alone looks after the eggs and chicks. She also has a very small comb and wattles (fleshy ornaments on the head that signal good health to rivals and potential mates) compared to the males.\n\n[[File:Gallus gallus female - Kaeng Krachan.jpg|thumb|alt=Drab female walking on stones|Female red junglefowl]]\nDuring their mating season, the male birds announce their presence with the well known \"cock-a-doodle-doo\" call or [[crowing]].<ref name=\":1\" />  Within flocks, only dominant males crow.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Collias, N. E.|first=N. E.|last2=Saichuae|first2=P.|date=1967|title=Ecology of the red jungle fowl in Thailand and Malaya with reference to the origin of domestication|url=http://www.siamese-heritage.org/nhbsspdf/vol021-030/NHBSS_022_1-2n_Collias_EcologyOfTheRedJ.pdf|journal=Natural History Bulletin of the Siam Society|volume=22|pages=189\u2013209|via=}}</ref> Male red junglefowl have a shorter crowing sound than domestic roosters; the call cuts off abruptly at the end.<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.wildsingapore.com/wildfacts/vertebrates/birds/gallus.htm Wild Singapore: Red Junglefowl], updated 9 October, accessed 1 January 2014.</ref> This serves both to attract potential mates and to make other male birds in the area aware of the risk of fighting a breeding competitor. A spur on the lower leg just behind and above the foot serves in such fighting. Their call structure is complex and they have distinctive alarm calls for aerial and ground predators to which others react appropriately.<ref>{{Citation|last=Collias|first=N. E.|title=The vocal repertoire of the red junglefowl: A spectrographic classification and the code of communication|journal=[[The Condor (journal)|The Condor]]|volume=89|issue=3|pages=510\u2013524|year=1987|postscript=|doi=10.2307/1368641|jstor=1368641}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Evans|first=C. S.|title=Effects of apparent size and speed on the response of chickens, ''Gallus gallus'', to computer-generated simulations of aerial predators|journal=[[Animal Behaviour (journal)|Animal Behaviour]]|volume=46|issue=1|pages=1\u201311|year=1993|postscript=|doi=10.1006/anbe.1993.1156|last2=Macedonia|first2=J. M.|last3=Marler|first3=P.|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/feb9c4cd783e89b5f35dc00ba4773059f3a335b2}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe range of the wild form stretches from India eastwards across [[Indochina]] and southern [[China]], into [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], the [[Philippines]], and [[Indonesia]]. Junglefowl were one of three main animals (along with the domesticated [[pig]]s and [[dogs]]) carried by early [[Austronesian peoples]] from [[Island Southeast Asia]] in their voyages to the islands of [[Oceania]] in prehistory, starting at around 5,000 [[Before Present|BP]]. Today their ancient descendants are found throughout [[Micronesia]], [[Melanesia]], and [[Polynesia]].<ref name=\"Piper\">{{cite book|first1=Philip J. |last1=Piper|editor1-first=Philip J. |editor1-last=Piper |editor2-first=Hirofumi |editor2-last=Matsumura |editor3-first=David |editor3-last=Bulbeck|title =New Perspectives in Southeast Asian and Pacific Prehistory|chapter =The Origins and Arrival of the Earliest Domestic Animals in Mainland and Island Southeast Asia: A Developing Story of Complexity|publisher =ANU Press|volume=45|series =terra australis|year =2017|page=|isbn =9781760460945|chapter-url =http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/n2320/html/ch15.xhtml}}</ref>\n\nRed junglefowl prefer disturbed habitats and edges, both natural and human-created.\u00a0Apparently the forage<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bump|first=G.|last2=Bohl|date=1961|title=Red Junglefowl and Kalij Pheasants|url=|journal=US Fish and Wildlife Service, Washington D.C., Special Scientific Reports, Wildlife|volume=No. 62|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnson|first=R. A.|date=1963|title=Habitat preferences and behavior of breeding jungle fowl in central western Thailand|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/128063|journal=Wilson Bulletin|volume=75|pages=270\u2013272|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> and thick cover in these sorts of areas are attractive to junglefowl, especially nesting females<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=N. .E.|last2=Collias|first2=E. C.|date=1967|title=A field study of the red jungle fowl in North-central India|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v069n04/p0360-p0386.pdf|journal=Condor|volume=69|issue=4|pages=360\u2013386|via=|doi=10.2307/1366199|jstor=1366199}}</ref>.\u00a0Junglefowl use logged and regenerating forests<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Datta|first=A.|date=2000|title=Pheasant abundance in selectively logged and unlogged forests of western Arunachal Pradesh, Northeast India|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/189503#page/195/mode/1up|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=97|pages=177\u2013183|via=}}</ref> and often are found near human settlement <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=A monograph of the Pheasants|last=Beebe|first=W.|publisher=Witherby & Co.|year=1921|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref> and areas regenerating from slash-and-burn cultivation <ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Areas burned to promote bamboo growth also attract junglefowl because bamboo seeds are more available<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. In some areas, red junglefowl are absent from silvicultural <ref name=\":5\" /> and rubber <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Abdullah|first=Z.|last2=Babjee|first2=S. A.|date=1982|title=Habitat preference of the Red Junglefowl (Gallus gallus)|url=|journal=Malaysian Applied Biology|volume=11|pages=59\u201363|via=}}</ref> plantations, but elsewhere they occur in both tea and palm-oil plantations <ref name=\":7\" />. In Selangor Province, Malaysia, palm foliage provides suitable cover, and palm oil fruit provides adequate food<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Arshad|first=Z.|last2=Zakaria|first2=M.|date=1999|title=Breeding ecology of red junglefowl (Gallus gallus spadiceus) in Malaysia|url=|journal=Malayan Nature Journal|volume=53|pages=355\u2013365|via=}}</ref>.\u00a0 The palms also offer an array of roost sites, from the low perches (~4 m) favored by females with chicks to the higher perches (up to 12 m) used by other adults<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arshad|first=Z.|last2=Zakaria|first2=M.|last3=Sajap|first3=A. S.|last4=Ismail|first4=A.|date=2001|title=Roosting ecology of red jungle fowl (Gallus gallus spadiceus) in oil palm plantation|url=|journal=Pakistan Journal of Scientific and Industrial Research|volume=44|pages=347\u2013350|via=}}</ref>.\n\nRed junglefowl drink surface water when it is available, but they apparently do not require it.\u00a0 Birds in North Central India visit water holes frequently during the dry season, although not all junglefowl in the region live close enough to water to do so<ref name=\":4\" />. Population densities may be lower, however, where surface water is limited<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n[[File:Red Junglefowl.jpg|thumb|alt=Colorful male on forest floor|Male red junglefowl]]\n\nRed junglefowl regularly bathe in dust to keep the right balance of oil in their plumage. The dust absorbs extra oil and subsequently falls off.<ref>Brinkley, Edward S., and Jane Beatson. \"Fascinating Feathers .\" Birds. Pleasantville, N.Y.: Reader's Digest Children's Books, 2000. 15. Print.</ref>\n\nFlight in these birds is almost purely confined to reaching their roosting areas at sunset in trees or any other high and relatively safe places free from ground predators, and for escape from immediate danger through the day.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nDominant male junglefowl appear to defend a territory against other dominant males, and the size of the territories has been inferred based on the proximity of roosts.\u00a0 Beebe<ref name=\":6\" /> concluded that territories were rather small, especially as compared to some of the pheasants with which he was familiar.\u00a0 This was supported by Collias and Collias,<ref name=\":4\" /> who reported that adjacent roost sites can be as close as 100 meters. Within flocks, male red junglefowl exhibit dominance hierarchies and dominant males tend to have larger combs than subordinate males.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Parker|first=Timothy H.|last2=Knapp|first2=Rosemary|last3=Rosenfield|first3=Jonathan A.|date=2002|title=Social mediation of sexually selected ornamentation and steroid hormone levels in male junglefowl|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=291\u2013298|doi=10.1006/anbe.2002.3050}}</ref> Red junglefowl typically live in flocks of one to a few males and several females. Males are more likely to occur alone than are females.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Hayashi|first2=Y.|last3=Kattel|first3=B.|last4=Shotake|first4=T.|last5=Kawamoto|first5=Y.|last6=Adachi|first6=A.|last7=Maeda|first7=Y.|date=1990|title=Morphological and ecological studies on the red jungle fowl in Nepal, the first and second investigations in 1986 and 1988|url=|journal=Japanese Journal of Zootechnical Science|volume=61|pages=79\u201388|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Hayashi|first2=Y|last3=Shotake|first3=T.|last4=Maeda|first4=Y.|last5=Yamamoto|first5=Y.|last6=Kurosawa|first6=Y.|last7=Douge|first7=K.|last8=Hongo|first8=A.|date=1992|title=Morphological identification and ecology of the red jungle fowl in Nepal|url=|journal=Animal Science and Technology (Japan)|volume=63|pages=256\u2013269|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Rerkamnuaychoke|first2=W.|last3=Tung|first3=D. G.|last4=Saignaleus|first4=S.|last5=Okamoto|first5=S.|last6=Kawamoto|first6=Y.|last7=Kimura|first7=J.|last8=Kawabe|first8=K.|last9=Tsunekawa|first9=N.|last10=Otaka|first10=H.|last11=Hayashi|first11=Y.|date=2000|title=Morphological identification and ecology of the red jungle fowl in Thailand, Laos, and Vietnam|url=|journal=Animal Science Journal|volume=71|pages=470\u2013480|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Red junglefowl hm.jpg|thumb|right|alt=refer to caption|Illustration of male and female red junglefowl]]\n\n=== Breeding ===\n[[File:Gallus gallus MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.5.11.jpg|thumb| ''Gallus gallus'' - [[MHNT]]]]\nMales make a food-related display called \"tidbitting\", performed upon finding food in the presence of a female.<ref>{{Citation|title=Animal Behaviour Lab Dr Chris Evans|date=15 November 2006|url=http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502204041/http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/index.html|url-status=dead|publisher=Galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au|accessdate=22 April 2009|archive-date=2 May 2009}}</ref> The display is composed of coaxing, cluck-like calls, and eye-catching bobbing and twitching motions of the head and neck. During the performance, the male repeatedly picks up and drops the food item with his beak. The display usually ends when the hen takes the food item either from the ground or directly from the male's beak. Mating then sometimes occurs.<ref>{{Citation|title=Home|url=http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/~kls/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211031651/http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/~kls/|url-status=dead|publisher=Galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au|accessdate=22 April 2009|archive-date=11 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn many areas, red junglefowl breed during the dry portion of the year, typically winter or spring. This is true in parts of India, Nepal, Thailand, Vietnam, and Laos<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />. However, year-round breeding by red junglefowl has been documented in palm-oil plantations in Malaysia<ref name=\":8\" /> and also may occur elsewhere <ref name=\":10\" />. During the laying period, red junglefowl females lay an egg every day. Eggs take 21 days to develop. Chicks fledge in about 4 to 5 weeks, and at 12 weeks old they are chased out of the group by their mother \u2014 at which point they start a new group or join an existing one. Sexual maturity is reached at 5 months, with females taking slightly longer than males to reach maturity.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDominant males attempt to maintain exclusive reproductive access to females, though females chose to mate with subordinate males about 40% of the time in a free-ranging feral flock in San Diego, USA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=Nicholas E.|last2=Collias|first2=Elsie C.|date=1996|title=Social organization of a red junglefowl,Gallus gallus, population related to evolution theory|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=51|issue=6|pages=1337\u20131354|doi=10.1006/anbe.1996.0137}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=Nicholas E.|last2=Collias|first2=Elsie C.|last3=Hunsaker|first3=Don|last4=Minning|first4=Lory|date=1966|title=Locality fixation, mobility and social organization within an unconfined population of red jungle fowl|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=14|issue=4|pages=550\u2013559|doi=10.1016/S0003-3472(66)80059-3|pmid=6008475}}</ref>. \n\n=== Diet ===\nRed junglefowl are attracted to areas with ripe fruit or seeds<ref name=\":4\" />, including fruit plantations<ref name=\":7\" />, fields of domestic grain<ref name=\":6\" />, and stands of bamboo<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Although junglefowl typically eat fallen fruits and seeds on the ground, they occasionally forage in trees by perching on branches and feeding on hanging fruit<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Fruits and seeds of scores of plant species have been identified from junglefowl crops, along with leaves, roots, and tubers<ref name=\":2\" />. In addition, red junglefowl capture a wide variety of arthropods, other invertebrates, and vertebrates such as small lizards. Even mammalian feces may be consumed<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Many of these items are taken opportunistically as the birds forage, although some arthropods, such as termites, are taken in large quantities; about 1,000 individual termites have been found in a single crop<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. Plant materials constitute a higher proportion of the diet of adult red junglefowl than do arthropods and other animals.\u00a0 In contrast, chicks eat mostly adult and larval insects, earthworms, and only occasional plant material<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\n==Relationship to humans==\n[[File:Junglefowl on tree.jpg|thumb|alt=refer to caption|Male red junglefowl crowing on a tree branch]]\n{{See also|Chicken}}\nThe red junglefowl was domesticated for human use well around 8,000 years ago<ref name = Lawal /> as subspecies ''Gallus gallus domesticus.'' Known as [[chicken|chickens]], they are a major source of food for humans. However, undomesticated red junglefowls still represent an important source of meat and eggs in their endemic range. The undomesticated form is sometimes used in [[Cock-Fighting|cock-fighting]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Timeline of domestication ===\nIn 2012, a study examined [[mitochondrial DNA]] recovered from ancient bones from Europe, [[Thailand]], the Pacific, and [[Chile]], and from Spanish colonial sites in [[Florida]] and the [[Dominican Republic]], in directly dated samples originating in Europe at 1,000 [[Before Present|BP]] and in the Pacific at 3,000 BP. Chicken was primarily domesticated from red junglefowl, with subsequent genetic contributions from [[grey junglefowl]], [[Sri Lankan junglefowl]], and [[green junglefowl]].<ref name = Lawal /> Domestication occurred about 8,000 years ago, as based on molecular evidence<ref name = Lawal /> from a common ancestor flock in the bird's natural range, and then proceeded in waves both east and west. Other archaeology evidence suggest domestication date around 7,400 BP from the Chishan site, in the [[Hebei province]] of China. However, domestication event in China has now been disputed by several studies citing unfavourable weather condition at the time<ref name=Peters>{{ cite journal | last1=Peters | first1=J. | display-authors=etal  | year=2015 | title=Questioning new answers regarding Holocene chicken domestication in China | journal=PNAS | volume=112 | issue=19 | pages=E2415 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1503579112 | doi-access=free | pmid=25886773 | pmc=4434763 | bibcode=2015PNAS..112E2415P }}</ref><ref name=Peng>{{ cite journal | last1=Peng | first1=M-S. | display-authors=etal  | year=2015 | title=Caveats about interpretation of ancient chicken mtDNAs from northern China | journal=PNAS | volume=112 | issue=16 | pages=E1970\u2013E1971 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1501151112 | doi-access=free | pmid=25795243 | pmc=4413316 | bibcode=2015PNAS..112E1970P }}</ref>. In the [[Ganges]] region of India, red junglefowl were being used by humans as early as 7,000 years ago. No domestic chicken remains older than 4,000 years have been identified in the [[Indus Valley]], and the antiquity of chickens recovered from excavations at [[Mohenjodaro]] is still debated.<ref name=\"Storey\">{{cite journal|title=Investigating the global dispersal of chickens in prehistory using ancient mitochondrial DNA signatures|author=Storey, A.A. |lastauthoramp=yes |journal=PLoS ONE|year=2012|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39171|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039171|display-authors=etal|pmid=22848352|pmc=3405094|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739171S }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox genome\n| image =\n| caption =\n| taxId =  111\n| ploidy = diploid\n| chromosomes = 78\n| size =\n| year =  2012\n| organelle =\n| organelle-size =\n| organelle-year =\n}}\n\n==Hybridisation==\nThe other three members of the genus \u2014 [[Sri Lanka junglefowl]] (''G. lafayetii''), [[grey junglefowl]] (''G. sonneratii''), and the [[green junglefowl]] (''G. varius'') \u2014 do not usually produce fertile hybrids with the red junglefowl.  However, supporting the hypothesis of a hybrid origin, research published in 2008 found that the gene responsible for the yellow skin of the domestic chicken most likely originated from the closely related grey junglefowl and not from the red junglefowl.<ref name = Eriksson /> Similarly, a 2020 study that analysed the whole genomes of [[Sri Lanka junglefowl]], [[grey junglefowl]], and the [[green junglefowl]] found strong [[Introgression|introgressive]] hybridisation events in different populations of indigenous village chickens.<ref name = Lawal /> The study also shows that 71\u201379% of red junglefowl DNA is shared with the domestic chicken.<ref name = Lawal /> A culturally significant hybrid between the red junglefowl and the green junglefowl in Indonesia is known as the ''[[bekisar]]''.\n\n== Status ==\nWild-type red junglefowl are thought to be facing threats due to hybridisation at forest edges, where domesticated free-ranging chickens are common.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/NDG/RJFbySPPA.html |title=Concerns for the genetic integrity and conservation status of the red junglefowl |author=I. Lehr Brisbin Jr. |location= |publisher=FeatherSite |accessdate=19 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/SPPA/SPPA.html |title=Society for the Preservation of Poultry Antiquities |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918234432/http://www.feathersite.com/Poultry/SPPA/SPPA.html |archivedate=18 September 2007  }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/NDG/BRKRedJF.html |title=Red Junglefowl (Gallus gallus) page & links}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/43115306-6278-49db-b761-9f7700fe64f9-9.html |title=Morphological and Behavioral Characteristics of Genetically Pure Indian Red Junglefowl, Gallus gallus murghi |author=Tomas P. Condon |accessdate=19 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629015245/http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/43115306-6278-49db-b761-9f7700fe64f9-9.html |archivedate=29 June 2007  }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.cvpws.com/junglefowl2.html |title=Hawkins, W.P. (n.d.). Carolinas/Virginia Pheasant & Waterfowl Society. Red Junglefowl \u2013 Pure Strain |accessdate=19 September 2007 |publisher=Cvpws.com}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Gallus_gallus.html |title=Gautier, Z. 2002. Gallus gallus (On-line), Animal Diversity Web. Accessed 19 September 2007 |publisher=Animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu |date= |accessdate=22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wildlifetrustofindia.org/html/news/2006/060113_red_jungle_fowl.html |title=Genetic invasion threatens red jungle fowl |publisher=Wildlife Trust of India, New Delhi |date=9 January 2006 |accessdate=19 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105220823/http://www.wildlifetrustofindia.org/html/news/2006/060113_red_jungle_fowl.html |archive-date=5 November 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.birdlife.org/news/news/2000/06/9.html |title=Red Junglefowl genetically swamped |date=1 June 2000 |quote=According to some scientists, truly wild populations of the red junglefowl ''Gallus gallus'' are either extinct or in grave danger of extinction due to introgression of genes from domestic or feral chickens |journal=Tragopan No. 12, P. 10, World Birdwatch 22 (2) |accessdate=19 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=246&m=0 |title=Red Junglefowl \u2013 Species factsheet: Gallus gallus |publisher=BirdLife International |year=2007 |work=BirdLife Species Factsheet |accessdate=20 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |year=1999 |title=Genetic endangerment of wild red junglefowl (Gallus gallus) |journal=Bird Conservation International |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=387\u2013394 |author1=Peterson, A.T. |author2=Brisbin, I. L. Jr. |lastauthoramp=yes |doi=10.1017/s0959270900002148|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{citation |author1=Brisbin, I. L. Jr. |year=1969 |title=Behavioral differentiation of wildness in two strains of Red Junglefowl (abstract) |journal=Am. Zool. |volume=9 |page=1072}}</ref> Nevertheless, they are classified by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] as a species of least concern.\n\n== References ==<!-- FieldianaZool106:58,114:1. -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies|Gallus gallus}}\n{{Commons category|Gallus gallus}}\n* [http://www.uniaga.com/2013/09/ayam-hutan-asli_21.html Malaysian Red Junglefowl]\n* Red Junglefowl: [http://www.uniaga.com/2014/08/perbezaan-ayam-hutan-merah-asli-dan.html Pure-bred v/s Cross-bred]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060629065946/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Gallus_gallus/ ARKive \u2013 images and movies of the Red Junglefowl ''(Gallus gallus)'']\n* [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=246&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110528042427/http://tommyspetparadise.webs.com/sandiegozoorjf.htm Red Junglefowl]\n* View the [http://www.ensembl.org/Gallus_gallus/Info/Index/ red junglefowl genome] in [[Ensembl]]\n* {{UCSC genomes|galGal4}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bikOAAAAQAAJ&dq=illustrated%20birds&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false Gallus bankiva]'' (illustration) in [[Sir William Jardine]], ''The natural history of gallinaceous birds: Vol. I.'', published by W. H. Lizars, and Stirling and Kenney, 1834; at Google Books.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002133055/http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/ Reference guide to the four species of the genus Gallus, commonly known as junglefowl. Contains information and photographs of each of the species]\n* [http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Earth/Flora__Fauna/Ancestors_of_chickens_studied_for_conservation/articleshow/3336847.cms Ancestors of chickens studied for conservation; 7 August 2008; The Economic Times, Times of India]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q184774}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:junglefowl, red}}\n[[Category:Junglefowls|red junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Birds of India]]\n[[Category:Birds of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Birds of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eastern Himalaya]]\n[[Category:Birds of South China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|red junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|red junglefowl]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of bird; wild origin of the domesticated chicken}}\n{{Redirect|Gallus gallus|other subspecies|Chicken}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Red junglefowl\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22679199/92806965 |title=''Gallus gallus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Red Junglefowl - Thailand.jpg\n| image_alt = Male red junglefowl walking across forest floor\n| genus = Gallus\n| species = gallus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Gallus gallus map.jpg\n| range_map_alt = World map showing range confined to Southeast Asia\n| range_map_caption = Red junglefowl range\n| synonyms = ''Phasianus gallus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''red junglefowl''' (''Gallus gallus'') is a [[tropical]] bird in the family [[Phasianidae]]. It ranges across much of [[Southeast Asia]] and parts of [[South Asia]]. Red junglefowl are the primary progenitor of the domestic [[chicken]] (''Gallus gallus domesticus''), but the [[grey junglefowl]], [[Sri Lankan junglefowl]] and [[green junglefowl]] have also contributed genetic materials to the gene pool of the domestic chicken.<ref name=Lawal>{{ cite journal | last1=Lawal | first1=RA. | display-authors=etal  | year=2020 | title=The wild species genome ancestry of domestic chickens | journal=BMC Biology | volume=18 | issue=13 | pages=13 | doi=10.1186/s12915-020-0738-1 | doi-access=free | pmid=32050971 }}</ref><ref name=\"Eriksson\">{{Citation |doi=10.1371/journal.pgen.1000010.eor |pmid=18454198 |author1=Eriksson, Jonas |author2=Larson, Greger |author3=Gunnarsson, Ulrika |author4=Bed'hom, Bertrand |author5=Tixier-Boichard, Michele |author6=Str\u00f6mstedt, Lina |author7=Wright, Dominic |author8=Jungerius, Annemieke |author9=Vereijken, Addie |author10=Randi, Ettore |author11=Jensen, Per |author12=Andersson, Leif |title=Identification of the Yellow Skin Gene Reveals a Hybrid Origin of the Domestic Chicken |publisher=PLoS Genet |pages=e10 |volume=preprint |date=23 January 2008 |journal=PLoS Genetics |displayauthors=8 |issue=2008  |doi-access=free }}</ref> \n\nEvidence from the molecular level derived from whole-genome sequencing revealed that chicken was domesticated from red junglefowl about 8,000 years ago, with this domestication event involving multiple maternal origins.<ref name = Lawal /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{ cite journal | last1=Liu | first1=Y-P. | display-authors=etal  | year=2006 | title=Multiple Maternal Origins of Chickens: Out of the Asian Jungles | journal=Mol Phylogenet Evol | volume=38 | issue=1 | pages=12\u20139 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2005.09.014 | doi-access=free | pmid=16275023 }}</ref> Since then, their domestic form has spread around the world and is kept globally as a source of meat and eggs.<ref name=\"Storey\" />\n\n== Taxonomy and systematics ==\n{{main article|Junglefowl}}\nNumerous wild and domestic subspecies of ''Gallus gallus'' exist, including:\n* ''G. g. gallus'' \u2013 from [[Southeast Asia]]\n* ''G. g. bankiva'' \u2013 from [[Java]]\n* ''G. g. jabouillei'' \u2013 from [[Vietnam]]\n* ''G. g. murghi'' \u2013 from [[India]] and [[Bangladesh]]\n* ''G. g. spadiceus'' \u2013 from [[Burma]]\n* ''[[Chicken|G. g. domesticus]]'' \u2013 domestic chicken\n{{Cladogram\n|caption=[[Cladogram]] showing the species in the genus ''[[Gallus (genus)|Gallus]]''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Tiley | first1=G.P. | last2=Pandey | first2=A. | last3=Kimball | first3=R.T. | last4=Braun | first4=E.L. | last5=Burleigh | first5=J.G. | year=2020| title=Whole genome phylogeny of ''Gallus'': introgression and data\u2011type effects | journal=Avian Research | volume=11 | issue=7 | doi=10.1186/s40657-020-00194-w | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n|align=right\n|cladogram={{Cladex| style=font-size:80%;line-height:75%;width:320px;\n|label1=''Gallus''&nbsp; \n|1={{clade\n   |1={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Grey junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus sonneratii''\n         |2=[[Sri Lanka junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus lafayettii''\n         }}\n      |2=[[Red junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus gallus''\n      }}\n    |2=[[Green junglefowl]] \u2013 ''Gallus varius''\n    }}\n}}\n}}\n\n== Description ==\nThe [[nominate race]] of red junglefowl has a mix of feather colours, with orange, brown, red, gold, grey, white, olive and even metallic green plumage. The tail of the male roosters can grow up to {{Convert|28|cm|in|abbr=}}, and the whole bird may be as long as {{Convert|70|cm|in|abbr=}}. There are 14 tail feathers. A moult in June changes the bird's plumage to an eclipse pattern, which lasts through October. The male eclipse pattern includes a black feather in the middle of the back and small red-orange plumes spread across the body. Female eclipse plumage is generally indistinguishable from the plumage at other seasons, but the moulting schedule is the same as that of males.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Gallus_gallus/|title=Gallus gallus (red junglefowl)|last=Gautier|first=Zoe|website=Animal Diversity Web|language=en|access-date=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nCompared to the more familiar domestic chicken, the red junglefowl has a much smaller body mass (around 2\u00bc lbs (1 kg) in females and 3\u00bc lbs (1.5kg) in males) and is brighter in coloration.<ref name=\":0\" /> Junglefowl are also behaviourally different from domestic chickens, being naturally very shy of humans compared to the much tamer domesticated subspecies.\n\n===Sexual dimorphism===\nMale junglefowl are significantly larger than females and have brightly coloured decorative feathers. The male's tail is composed of long, arching feathers that initially look black, but shimmer with blue, purple, and green in direct light. He also has long, golden hackle feathers on his neck and on his back. The female's [[plumage]] is typical of this family of birds in being [[crypsis|cryptic]] and [[adaptation|adapted]] for [[camouflage]]. She alone looks after the eggs and chicks. She also has a very small comb and wattles (fleshy ornaments on the head that signal good health to rivals and potential mates) compared to the males.\n\n[[File:Gallus gallus female - Kaeng Krachan.jpg|thumb|alt=Drab female walking on stones|Female red junglefowl]]\nDuring their mating season, the male birds announce their presence with the well known \"cock-a-doodle-doo\" call or [[crowing]].<ref name=\":1\" />  Within flocks, only dominant males crow.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Collias, N. E.|first=N. E.|last2=Saichuae|first2=P.|date=1967|title=Ecology of the red jungle fowl in Thailand and Malaya with reference to the origin of domestication|url=http://www.siamese-heritage.org/nhbsspdf/vol021-030/NHBSS_022_1-2n_Collias_EcologyOfTheRedJ.pdf|journal=Natural History Bulletin of the Siam Society|volume=22|pages=189\u2013209|via=}}</ref> Male red junglefowl have a shorter crowing sound than domestic roosters; the call cuts off abruptly at the end.<ref name=\":1\">[http://www.wildsingapore.com/wildfacts/vertebrates/birds/gallus.htm Wild Singapore: Red Junglefowl], updated 9 October, accessed 1 January 2014.</ref> This serves both to attract potential mates and to make other male birds in the area aware of the risk of fighting a breeding competitor. A spur on the lower leg just behind and above the foot serves in such fighting. Their call structure is complex and they have distinctive alarm calls for aerial and ground predators to which others react appropriately.<ref>{{Citation|last=Collias|first=N. E.|title=The vocal repertoire of the red junglefowl: A spectrographic classification and the code of communication|journal=[[The Condor (journal)|The Condor]]|volume=89|issue=3|pages=510\u2013524|year=1987|postscript=|doi=10.2307/1368641|jstor=1368641}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Evans|first=C. S.|title=Effects of apparent size and speed on the response of chickens, ''Gallus gallus'', to computer-generated simulations of aerial predators|journal=[[Animal Behaviour (journal)|Animal Behaviour]]|volume=46|issue=1|pages=1\u201311|year=1993|postscript=|doi=10.1006/anbe.1993.1156|last2=Macedonia|first2=J. M.|last3=Marler|first3=P.|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/feb9c4cd783e89b5f35dc00ba4773059f3a335b2}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe range of the wild form stretches from India eastwards across [[Indochina]] and southern [[China]], into [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], the [[Philippines]], and [[Indonesia]]. Junglefowl were one of three main animals (along with the domesticated [[pig]]s and [[dogs]]) carried by early [[Austronesian peoples]] from [[Island Southeast Asia]] in their voyages to the islands of [[Oceania]] in prehistory, starting at around 5,000 [[Before Present|BP]]. Today their ancient descendants are found throughout [[Micronesia]], [[Melanesia]], and [[Polynesia]].<ref name=\"Piper\">{{cite book|first1=Philip J. |last1=Piper|editor1-first=Philip J. |editor1-last=Piper |editor2-first=Hirofumi |editor2-last=Matsumura |editor3-first=David |editor3-last=Bulbeck|title =New Perspectives in Southeast Asian and Pacific Prehistory|chapter =The Origins and Arrival of the Earliest Domestic Animals in Mainland and Island Southeast Asia: A Developing Story of Complexity|publisher =ANU Press|volume=45|series =terra australis|year =2017|page=|isbn =9781760460945|chapter-url =http://press-files.anu.edu.au/downloads/press/n2320/html/ch15.xhtml}}</ref>\n\nRed junglefowl prefer disturbed habitats and edges, both natural and human-created.\u00a0Apparently the forage<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bump|first=G.|last2=Bohl|date=1961|title=Red Junglefowl and Kalij Pheasants|url=|journal=US Fish and Wildlife Service, Washington D.C., Special Scientific Reports, Wildlife|volume=No. 62|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnson|first=R. A.|date=1963|title=Habitat preferences and behavior of breeding jungle fowl in central western Thailand|url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/128063|journal=Wilson Bulletin|volume=75|pages=270\u2013272|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> and thick cover in these sorts of areas are attractive to junglefowl, especially nesting females<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=N. .E.|last2=Collias|first2=E. C.|date=1967|title=A field study of the red jungle fowl in North-central India|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v069n04/p0360-p0386.pdf|journal=Condor|volume=69|issue=4|pages=360\u2013386|via=|doi=10.2307/1366199|jstor=1366199}}</ref>.\u00a0Junglefowl use logged and regenerating forests<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Datta|first=A.|date=2000|title=Pheasant abundance in selectively logged and unlogged forests of western Arunachal Pradesh, Northeast India|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/189503#page/195/mode/1up|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=97|pages=177\u2013183|via=}}</ref> and often are found near human settlement <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=A monograph of the Pheasants|last=Beebe|first=W.|publisher=Witherby & Co.|year=1921|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref> and areas regenerating from slash-and-burn cultivation <ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Areas burned to promote bamboo growth also attract junglefowl because bamboo seeds are more available<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. In some areas, red junglefowl are absent from silvicultural <ref name=\":5\" /> and rubber <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Abdullah|first=Z.|last2=Babjee|first2=S. A.|date=1982|title=Habitat preference of the Red Junglefowl (Gallus gallus)|url=|journal=Malaysian Applied Biology|volume=11|pages=59\u201363|via=}}</ref> plantations, but elsewhere they occur in both tea and palm-oil plantations <ref name=\":7\" />. In Selangor Province, Malaysia, palm foliage provides suitable cover, and palm oil fruit provides adequate food<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Arshad|first=Z.|last2=Zakaria|first2=M.|date=1999|title=Breeding ecology of red junglefowl (Gallus gallus spadiceus) in Malaysia|url=|journal=Malayan Nature Journal|volume=53|pages=355\u2013365|via=}}</ref>.\u00a0 The palms also offer an array of roost sites, from the low perches (~4 m) favored by females with chicks to the higher perches (up to 12 m) used by other adults<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arshad|first=Z.|last2=Zakaria|first2=M.|last3=Sajap|first3=A. S.|last4=Ismail|first4=A.|date=2001|title=Roosting ecology of red jungle fowl (Gallus gallus spadiceus) in oil palm plantation|url=|journal=Pakistan Journal of Scientific and Industrial Research|volume=44|pages=347\u2013350|via=}}</ref>.\n\nRed junglefowl drink surface water when it is available, but they apparently do not require it.\u00a0 Birds in North Central India visit water holes frequently during the dry season, although not all junglefowl in the region live close enough to water to do so<ref name=\":4\" />. Population densities may be lower, however, where surface water is limited<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n[[File:Red Junglefowl.jpg|thumb|alt=Colorful male on forest floor|Male red junglefowl]]\n\nRed junglefowl regularly bathe in dust to keep the right balance of oil in their plumage. The dust absorbs extra oil and subsequently falls off.<ref>Brinkley, Edward S., and Jane Beatson. \"Fascinating Feathers .\" Birds. Pleasantville, N.Y.: Reader's Digest Children's Books, 2000. 15. Print.</ref>\n\nFlight in these birds is almost purely confined to reaching their roosting areas at sunset in trees or any other high and relatively safe places free from ground predators, and for escape from immediate danger through the day.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nDominant male junglefowl appear to defend a territory against other dominant males, and the size of the territories has been inferred based on the proximity of roosts.\u00a0 Beebe<ref name=\":6\" /> concluded that territories were rather small, especially as compared to some of the pheasants with which he was familiar.\u00a0 This was supported by Collias and Collias,<ref name=\":4\" /> who reported that adjacent roost sites can be as close as 100 meters. Within flocks, male red junglefowl exhibit dominance hierarchies and dominant males tend to have larger combs than subordinate males.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Parker|first=Timothy H.|last2=Knapp|first2=Rosemary|last3=Rosenfield|first3=Jonathan A.|date=2002|title=Social mediation of sexually selected ornamentation and steroid hormone levels in male junglefowl|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=291\u2013298|doi=10.1006/anbe.2002.3050}}</ref> Red junglefowl typically live in flocks of one to a few males and several females. Males are more likely to occur alone than are females.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Hayashi|first2=Y.|last3=Kattel|first3=B.|last4=Shotake|first4=T.|last5=Kawamoto|first5=Y.|last6=Adachi|first6=A.|last7=Maeda|first7=Y.|date=1990|title=Morphological and ecological studies on the red jungle fowl in Nepal, the first and second investigations in 1986 and 1988|url=|journal=Japanese Journal of Zootechnical Science|volume=61|pages=79\u201388|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Hayashi|first2=Y|last3=Shotake|first3=T.|last4=Maeda|first4=Y.|last5=Yamamoto|first5=Y.|last6=Kurosawa|first6=Y.|last7=Douge|first7=K.|last8=Hongo|first8=A.|date=1992|title=Morphological identification and ecology of the red jungle fowl in Nepal|url=|journal=Animal Science and Technology (Japan)|volume=63|pages=256\u2013269|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Nishida|first=T.|last2=Rerkamnuaychoke|first2=W.|last3=Tung|first3=D. G.|last4=Saignaleus|first4=S.|last5=Okamoto|first5=S.|last6=Kawamoto|first6=Y.|last7=Kimura|first7=J.|last8=Kawabe|first8=K.|last9=Tsunekawa|first9=N.|last10=Otaka|first10=H.|last11=Hayashi|first11=Y.|date=2000|title=Morphological identification and ecology of the red jungle fowl in Thailand, Laos, and Vietnam|url=|journal=Animal Science Journal|volume=71|pages=470\u2013480|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Red junglefowl hm.jpg|thumb|right|alt=refer to caption|Illustration of male and female red junglefowl]]\n\n=== Breeding ===\n[[File:Gallus gallus MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.5.11.jpg|thumb| ''Gallus gallus'' - [[MHNT]]]]\nMales make a food-related display called \"tidbitting\", performed upon finding food in the presence of a female.<ref>{{Citation|title=Animal Behaviour Lab Dr Chris Evans|date=15 November 2006|url=http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502204041/http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/index.html|url-status=dead|publisher=Galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au|accessdate=22 April 2009|archive-date=2 May 2009}}</ref> The display is composed of coaxing, cluck-like calls, and eye-catching bobbing and twitching motions of the head and neck. During the performance, the male repeatedly picks up and drops the food item with his beak. The display usually ends when the hen takes the food item either from the ground or directly from the male's beak. Mating then sometimes occurs.<ref>{{Citation|title=Home|url=http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/~kls/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211031651/http://galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au/~kls/|url-status=dead|publisher=Galliform.bhs.mq.edu.au|accessdate=22 April 2009|archive-date=11 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn many areas, red junglefowl breed during the dry portion of the year, typically winter or spring. This is true in parts of India, Nepal, Thailand, Vietnam, and Laos<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />. However, year-round breeding by red junglefowl has been documented in palm-oil plantations in Malaysia<ref name=\":8\" /> and also may occur elsewhere <ref name=\":10\" />. During the laying period, red junglefowl females lay an egg every day. Eggs take 21 days to develop. Chicks fledge in about 4 to 5 weeks, and at 12 weeks old they are chased out of the group by their mother \u2014 at which point they start a new group or join an existing one. Sexual maturity is reached at 5 months, with females taking slightly longer than males to reach maturity.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDominant males attempt to maintain exclusive reproductive access to females, though females chose to mate with subordinate males about 40% of the time in a free-ranging feral flock in San Diego, USA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=Nicholas E.|last2=Collias|first2=Elsie C.|date=1996|title=Social organization of a red junglefowl,Gallus gallus, population related to evolution theory|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=51|issue=6|pages=1337\u20131354|doi=10.1006/anbe.1996.0137}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Collias|first=Nicholas E.|last2=Collias|first2=Elsie C.|last3=Hunsaker|first3=Don|last4=Minning|first4=Lory|date=1966|title=Locality fixation, mobility and social organization within an unconfined population of red jungle fowl|journal=Animal Behaviour|language=en|volume=14|issue=4|pages=550\u2013559|doi=10.1016/S0003-3472(66)80059-3|pmid=6008475}}</ref>. \n\n=== Diet ===\nRed junglefowl are attracted to areas with ripe fruit or seeds<ref name=\":4\" />, including fruit plantations<ref name=\":7\" />, fields of domestic grain<ref name=\":6\" />, and stands of bamboo<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Although junglefowl typically eat fallen fruits and seeds on the ground, they occasionally forage in trees by perching on branches and feeding on hanging fruit<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Fruits and seeds of scores of plant species have been identified from junglefowl crops, along with leaves, roots, and tubers<ref name=\":2\" />. In addition, red junglefowl capture a wide variety of arthropods, other invertebrates, and vertebrates such as small lizards. Even mammalian feces may be consumed<ref name=\":2\" />.\u00a0 Many of these items are taken opportunistically as the birds forage, although some arthropods, such as termites, are taken in large quantities; about 1,000 individual termites have been found in a single crop<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" />. Plant materials constitute a higher proportion of the diet of adult red junglefowl than do arthropods and other animals.\u00a0 In contrast, chicks eat mostly adult and larval insects, earthworms, and only occasional plant material<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\n==Relationship to humans==\n[[File:Junglefowl on tree.jpg|thumb|alt=refer to caption|Male red junglefowl crowing on a tree branch]]\n{{See also|Chicken}}\nThe red junglefowl was domesticated for human use well over 5,000 years ago as subspecies ''Gallus gallus domesticus.'' Known as [[chicken|chickens]], they are a major source of food for humans. However, undomesticated red junglefowls still represent an important source of meat and eggs in their endemic range. The undomesticated form is sometimes used in [[Cock-Fighting|cock-fighting]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Timeline of domestication ===\nIn 2012, a study examined [[mitochondrial DNA]] recovered from ancient bones from Europe, [[Thailand]], the Pacific, and [[Chile]], and from Spanish colonial sites in [[Florida]] and the [[Dominican Republic]], in directly dated samples originating in Europe at 1,000 [[Before Present|BP]] and in the Pacific at 3,000 BP. Chicken was primarily domesticated from red junglefowl, with subsequent genetic contributions from [[grey junglefowl]], [[Sri Lankan junglefowl]], and [[green junglefowl]].<ref name = Lawal /> Domestication occurred about 8,000 years ago, as based on molecular evidence<ref name = Lawal /> from a common ancestor flock in the bird's natural range, and then proceeded in waves both east and west. Other archaeology evidence suggest domestication date around 7,400 BP from the Chishan site, in the [[Hebei province]] of China. However, domestication event in China has now been disputed by several studies citing unfavourable weather condition at the time<ref name=Peters>{{ cite journal | last1=Peters | first1=J. | display-authors=etal  | year=2015 | title=Questioning new answers regarding Holocene chicken domestication in China | journal=PNAS | volume=112 | issue=19 | pages=E2415 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1503579112 | doi-access=free | pmid=25886773 | pmc=4434763 | bibcode=2015PNAS..112E2415P }}</ref><ref name=Peng>{{ cite journal | last1=Peng | first1=M-S. | display-authors=etal  | year=2015 | title=Caveats about interpretation of ancient chicken mtDNAs from northern China | journal=PNAS | volume=112 | issue=16 | pages=E1970\u2013E1971 | doi=10.1073/pnas.1501151112 | doi-access=free | pmid=25795243 | pmc=4413316 | bibcode=2015PNAS..112E1970P }}</ref>. In the [[Ganges]] region of India, red junglefowl were being used by humans as early as 7,000 years ago. No domestic chicken remains older than 4,000 years have been identified in the [[Indus Valley]], and the antiquity of chickens recovered from excavations at [[Mohenjodaro]] is still debated.<ref name=\"Storey\">{{cite journal|title=Investigating the global dispersal of chickens in prehistory using ancient mitochondrial DNA signatures|author=Storey, A.A. |lastauthoramp=yes |journal=PLoS ONE|year=2012|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39171|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039171|display-authors=etal|pmid=22848352|pmc=3405094|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739171S }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox genome\n| image =\n| caption =\n| taxId =  111\n| ploidy = diploid\n| chromosomes = 78\n| size =\n| year =  2012\n| organelle =\n| organelle-size =\n| organelle-year =\n}}\n\n==Hybridisation==\nThe other three members of the genus \u2014 [[Sri Lanka junglefowl]] (''G. lafayetii''), [[grey junglefowl]] (''G. sonneratii''), and the [[green junglefowl]] (''G. varius'') \u2014 do not usually produce fertile hybrids with the red junglefowl.  However, supporting the hypothesis of a hybrid origin, research published in 2008 found that the gene responsible for the yellow skin of the domestic chicken most likely originated from the closely related grey junglefowl and not from the red junglefowl.<ref name = Eriksson /> A 2020 study that analysed the whole genome of Sri Lanka junglefowl, grey junglefowl, and green junglefowl found strong [[Introgression|introgressive]] hybridisation events in different populations of indigenous village chickens.<ref name = Lawal /> The study also shows that 71\u201379% of red junglefowl DNA is shared with the domestic chicken.<ref name = Lawal /> A culturally significant hybrid between the red junglefowl and the green junglefowl in Indonesia is known as the ''[[bekisar]]''.\n\n== Status ==\nWild-type red junglefowl are thought to be facing threats due to hybridisation at forest edges, where domesticated free-ranging chickens are common.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/NDG/RJFbySPPA.html |title=Concerns for the genetic integrity and conservation status of the red junglefowl |author=I. Lehr Brisbin Jr. |location= |publisher=FeatherSite |accessdate=19 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/SPPA/SPPA.html |title=Society for the Preservation of Poultry Antiquities |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918234432/http://www.feathersite.com/Poultry/SPPA/SPPA.html |archivedate=18 September 2007  }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.feathersite.com//Poultry/NDG/BRKRedJF.html |title=Red Junglefowl (Gallus gallus) page & links}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/43115306-6278-49db-b761-9f7700fe64f9-9.html |title=Morphological and Behavioral Characteristics of Genetically Pure Indian Red Junglefowl, Gallus gallus murghi |author=Tomas P. Condon |accessdate=19 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629015245/http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/43115306-6278-49db-b761-9f7700fe64f9-9.html |archivedate=29 June 2007  }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.cvpws.com/junglefowl2.html |title=Hawkins, W.P. (n.d.). Carolinas/Virginia Pheasant & Waterfowl Society. Red Junglefowl \u2013 Pure Strain |accessdate=19 September 2007 |publisher=Cvpws.com}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Gallus_gallus.html |title=Gautier, Z. 2002. Gallus gallus (On-line), Animal Diversity Web. Accessed 19 September 2007 |publisher=Animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu |date= |accessdate=22 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wildlifetrustofindia.org/html/news/2006/060113_red_jungle_fowl.html |title=Genetic invasion threatens red jungle fowl |publisher=Wildlife Trust of India, New Delhi |date=9 January 2006 |accessdate=19 September 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071105220823/http://www.wildlifetrustofindia.org/html/news/2006/060113_red_jungle_fowl.html |archive-date=5 November 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.birdlife.org/news/news/2000/06/9.html |title=Red Junglefowl genetically swamped |date=1 June 2000 |quote=According to some scientists, truly wild populations of the red junglefowl ''Gallus gallus'' are either extinct or in grave danger of extinction due to introgression of genes from domestic or feral chickens |journal=Tragopan No. 12, P. 10, World Birdwatch 22 (2) |accessdate=19 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=246&m=0 |title=Red Junglefowl \u2013 Species factsheet: Gallus gallus |publisher=BirdLife International |year=2007 |work=BirdLife Species Factsheet |accessdate=20 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{citation |year=1999 |title=Genetic endangerment of wild red junglefowl (Gallus gallus) |journal=Bird Conservation International |volume=9 |issue=4 |pages=387\u2013394 |author1=Peterson, A.T. |author2=Brisbin, I. L. Jr. |lastauthoramp=yes |doi=10.1017/s0959270900002148|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{citation |author1=Brisbin, I. L. Jr. |year=1969 |title=Behavioral differentiation of wildness in two strains of Red Junglefowl (abstract) |journal=Am. Zool. |volume=9 |page=1072}}</ref> Nevertheless, they are classified by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] as a species of least concern.\n\n== References ==<!-- FieldianaZool106:58,114:1. -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikispecies|Gallus gallus}}\n{{Commons category|Gallus gallus}}\n* [http://www.uniaga.com/2013/09/ayam-hutan-asli_21.html Malaysian Red Junglefowl]\n* Red Junglefowl: [http://www.uniaga.com/2014/08/perbezaan-ayam-hutan-merah-asli-dan.html Pure-bred v/s Cross-bred]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060629065946/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Gallus_gallus/ ARKive \u2013 images and movies of the Red Junglefowl ''(Gallus gallus)'']\n* [http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=246&m=0 BirdLife Species Factsheet]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110528042427/http://tommyspetparadise.webs.com/sandiegozoorjf.htm Red Junglefowl]\n* View the [http://www.ensembl.org/Gallus_gallus/Info/Index/ red junglefowl genome] in [[Ensembl]]\n* {{UCSC genomes|galGal4}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bikOAAAAQAAJ&dq=illustrated%20birds&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false Gallus bankiva]'' (illustration) in [[Sir William Jardine]], ''The natural history of gallinaceous birds: Vol. I.'', published by W. H. Lizars, and Stirling and Kenney, 1834; at Google Books.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002133055/http://www.wildfowl.uconn.edu/ Reference guide to the four species of the genus Gallus, commonly known as junglefowl. Contains information and photographs of each of the species]\n* [http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Earth/Flora__Fauna/Ancestors_of_chickens_studied_for_conservation/articleshow/3336847.cms Ancestors of chickens studied for conservation; 7 August 2008; The Economic Times, Times of India]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q184774}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:junglefowl, red}}\n[[Category:Junglefowls|red junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Birds of India]]\n[[Category:Birds of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Birds of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eastern Himalaya]]\n[[Category:Birds of South China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Southeast Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|red junglefowl]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|red junglefowl]]\n", "name_user": "Akinyanju", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update the based on the recent findings of the species", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_junglefowl"}
{"title_page": "Clueless (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1995 film by Amy Heckerling}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clueless\n| image          = Clueless film poster.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Amy Heckerling]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* [[Robert Lawrence (producer)|Robert Lawrence]]\n}}\n| writer         = Amy Heckerling\n| based on       = <!-- Do not add Emma here, was not a credited adaptation -->\n| starring       = [[Alicia Silverstone]]<!--Only Silverstone's name appears on the poster-->\n| music          = [[David Kitay]]\n| cinematography = [[Bill Pope]]\n| editing        = Debra Chiate\n| studio         = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1995|7|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 97:24--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/clueless-1970-1 | title=''Clueless'' (12) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=July 28, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $12 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://powergrid.thewrap.com/project/clueless|title=Clueless - PowerGrid|work=thewrap.com|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $56.6 million<ref name=BOMClueless/>\n}}\n'''''Clueless''''' is a 1995 American [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[Teen film|teen]] [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[Amy Heckerling]]. It stars [[Alicia Silverstone]], [[Stacey Dash]], [[Paul Rudd]], [[Dan Hedaya]], and [[Brittany Murphy]]. It was produced by [[Scott Rudin]] and [[Robert Lawrence (producer)|Robert Lawrence]]. It is loosely based on [[Jane Austen]]'s 1815 novel ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'', with a modern-day setting of [[Beverly Hills]].<ref>[http://www.jasna.org/persuasions/on-line/opno3/mazmanian.html Mazmanian, Melissa. \"Reviving ''Emma'' in a ''Clueless'' World: The Current Attraction to a Classic Structure.] Persuasions Online: Occasional Papers No. 3. Fall 1999. Jane Austen Society of North America website. Accessed November 12, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.australianhumanitiesreview.org/archive/Issue-August-1997/stern.html Stern, Lesley. \"Emma in Los Angeles\" ''Clueless'' as a remake of the book and the city.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006181505/http://www.australianhumanitiesreview.org/archive/Issue-August-1997/stern.html |date=October 6, 2013 }} Australian Humanities Review website, 1997. Accessed November 12, 2013.</ref> The plot centers on Cher Horowitz, a rich and beautiful high school student who befriends a new student named Tai Frasier and decides to give her a makeover.\n\n''Clueless'' was filmed in California over a 40-day schedule. The film's director studied real Beverly Hills high school students to understand how real teens in the 1990s talked and learn some appropriate slang terms.\n\nThe film grossed $56.1 million in the United States. It has received generally positive reviews from critics and is considered to be one of the [[List of films considered the best|best teen films of all time]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Clueless {{!}} Issue 109 {{!}} Philosophy Now|url = https://philosophynow.org/issues/109/Clueless|website = philosophynow.org|accessdate = 2015-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/07/05/an-oral-history-of-the-cult-classic-that-is-clueless/ |title=An oral history of the cult classic that is 'Clueless' |newspaper=New York Post |date=July 5, 2015 |author=Susannah Cahalan |accessdate=July 12, 2015|author-link=Susannah Cahalan }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chacha.com/gallery/3438/which-90s-films-are-cult-classics/33173 |title=Which 90s Films Are Cult Classics? |publisher=ChaCha |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713122440/http://www.chacha.com/gallery/3438/which-90s-films-are-cult-classics/33173 |archive-date=July 13, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neontommy.com/news/2014/07/5-cult-classic-films-never-get-old |title=5 Cult Classic Films That Never Get Old |work=Neon Tommy |date=July 21, 2014 |first=Ashley |last=Hawkins |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223080017/http://www.neontommy.com/news/2014/07/5-cult-classic-films-never-get-old |archive-date=February 23, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Clueless'' has developed a [[cult following]] and has a continuing legacy. The film was followed by a spin-off [[Clueless (TV series)|television sitcom]], [[Clueless (novels)|series of books]], and Paramount Studios has announced that they are producing a remake.\n\n==Plot==\nCher Horowitz lives in a Beverly Hills mansion with her father Mel, a $500-an-hour [[litigator]]; her mother died during a routine [[liposuction]] procedure when Cher was a baby. Cher is attractive, popular, and wealthy. She attends Bronson Alcott High School with her best friend, Dionne Davenport, who is also wealthy and beautiful. Dionne has a long-term relationship with popular student Murray; Cher claims that this is a pointless endeavor for Dionne.\n\nJosh, Cher's socially conscious ex-stepbrother, visits her during a break from college. They spar continually but playfully. She mocks his idealism, while he teases her for being selfish, vain and superficial, saying that her only direction in life is \"toward the mall\". Cher plays matchmaker for two hard-grading teachers at her school, Mr. Hall and Miss Geist. She facilitates the relationship between the teachers to make them relax their grading standards so she can renegotiate a bad grade on her report card. After she sees their newfound happiness, she realizes she enjoys doing good deeds. She then decides to give back to the community by \"adopting\" a \"tragically [[Hip (slang)|unhip]]\" new girl at school, Tai Frasier. Cher and Dionne give Tai a makeover, which gives Tai confidence and a sense of style. Cher also tries to extinguish the attraction between Tai and Travis Birkenstock, an amiable skateboarding slacker, and to steer her towards Elton, a popular and wealthy student.\n\nElton rejects Tai and fails to seduce Cher. A handsome new student at their school named Christian becomes Cher's target boyfriend. Murray explains to Cher and Dionne that Christian is gay. Despite the failure of this endeavor, Cher remains on friendly terms with Christian, primarily due to her admiration of his taste in art and fashion. Matters take a turn for the worse when Tai's newfound popularity strains her relationship with Cher. Cher's frustration escalates when she fails her driving test and cannot change the result. When she returns home, crushed, Tai confesses her feelings for Josh and wants Cher's help in pursuing him. Cher says Tai is not right for Josh and they quarrel. Their disagreement ends with Tai calling Cher a \"virgin who can't drive\". Feeling \"totally clueless\", Cher reflects on her priorities and her repeated failures to understand or appreciate the people in her life.\n\nAfter thinking about why she is bothered by Tai's interest in Josh, Cher realizes that she loves him. She begins making awkward but sincere efforts to live a more purposeful life, including captaining the school's [[Pismo Beach]] disaster relief effort. Cher and Josh eventually admit their feelings for one another, culminating in a tender kiss. Ultimately, Mr. Hall and Miss Geist wed; Cher's friendships with Tai and Dionne are solidified; Tai and Travis are in love and Cher catches the wedding bouquet, helping Josh win a $200 bet. She embraces Josh and they kiss.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Anchor|Cast}}\n{{See also|List of Clueless characters}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Alicia Silverstone]] as Cher Horowitz\n* [[Stacey Dash]] as Dionne Davenport\n* [[Brittany Murphy]] as Tai Frasier\n* [[Paul Rudd]] as Josh Lucas\n* [[Dan Hedaya]] as Melvin \"Mel\" Horowitz (\"Hamilton\" in the credits)\n* [[Elisa Donovan]] as Amber Mariens\n* [[Justin Walker (actor)|Justin Walker]] as Christian Stovitz\n*[[Wallace Shawn]] as Mr. Wendell Hall\n*[[Twink Caplan]] as Ms. Toby Geist\n*[[Julie Brown]] as Coach Millie Stoeger\n*[[Donald Faison]] as Murray Duvall, Dionne's long-term boyfriend\n*[[Breckin Meyer]] as Travis Birkenstock\n*[[Jeremy Sisto]] as Elton Tiscia\n*[[Nicole Bilderback]] as Summer Han\n*Sean Holland as Lawrence\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAccording to the special feature titled \"''Creative Writing''\", Heckerling describes the origins of ''Clueless'' as follows:\n{{quote|I went to [[20th Century Fox]] and they said \"We want you to do something about teenagers.\" And I thought \"I'm so tired about doing stuff about teenagers.\" But they said, \"We want you to do something about the 'in' crowd.\" I thought \"I'll do it if I can make fun of them.\" So, we developed this script. It was a pilot for a TV show. And it was about this girl that was completely happy, no matter what happened. And I was really getting into that kind of character. But nothing happened with it. They passed on it, they didn't get it. And a number of things were sort of falling through. I was just getting very frustrated. So I switched agents and when I had my new agent, they said: \"What have you been working on?\" So I showed Ken Stovitz, one of the agents there, this pilot. And he said, \"This is too good for TV. You should make this into a feature.\"<ref name=\"Creative\">{{cite news|url=https://vimeo.com/343465997|title=''Clueless'' - Creative Writing|publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>}}\n\nShe follows up on the connections to the [[Jane Austen]] novel, ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'':\n{{quote|I started to think, \"What's the larger context for that kind of a 'nothing can go wrong' 'always looks through rose colored glasses' kind of girl?\" And I remembered ''Emma'', which I'd read in college. So, I took it out and reread it, and I said: \"Unconsciously, I've been writing an Emma-like character.\" Because I've always loved it and part of it had sort of stored it away in my brain... So I really related to her and got into it. And the plot was so brilliantly laid out in ''Emma''. So I tried to take all the things that were in this sort of pretty 1800s world and see what would that be like if it was in [[Beverly Hills]].<ref name=\"Creative\" />}} \n\nAssociate producer [[Twink Caplan]] recalls what the proposed TV show's initial title:\n{{quote|''No Worries'' was the original television script that Amy wrote. Then, we went to ''I Was a Teenage Teenager'' because with every new draft that Amy writes, she picks a whole new title.<ref name=\"Creative\" />}}\n\nFox picked up the picture, but put the film in a [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]]. The male studio heads wanted Heckerling to rewrite the script so that fewer women would feature. Six months later, the script made its way to producer [[Scott Rudin]]. Rudin like the script and it was the subject of a bidding war, with [[Paramount Pictures]] beating out the other studios. Heckerling was excited, as Paramount owned several major youth-centered channels, such as [[MTV]] and [[Nickelodeon]], which was suited to the film's target demographic.<ref name=\"Creative\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Westfield Fashion Square.JPG|Westfield Fashion Square|thumb|150px|The Westfield Fashion Square]]\nPrincipal photography for the film took place between November 21 and December 31, 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Alicia Silverstone Stars in 'Clueless,' A Romantic Comedy Written and Directed by Amy Heckelilng|url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ALICIA+SILVERSTONE+STARS+IN+'CLUELESS,'+A+ROMANTIC+COMEDY+WRITTEN+AND...-a015982332|website = thefreelibrary.com|access-date = 2016-02-05}}</ref> The film had a 40-day filming schedule. Producers sat in on classes at [[Beverly Hills High School]] to get a feel for the student culture. Herb Hall, the real drama teacher at Beverly Hills High School, had a short scene as the principal in the film. Scenes depicting the high school campus, including the tennis courts, the outdoor cafeteria, the quad, and various classrooms were filmed at [[Occidental College]] in [[Los Angeles]]. The mall scenes were filmed at [[Westfield Fashion Square]] in [[Sherman Oaks, California]].\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{Anchor|Box office}}\nThe film became a surprise [[sleeper hit]] of 1995. ''Clueless'' opened in 1,653 theaters on July 19, 1995 and grossed $10,612,443 on its opening weekend, which led to a ranking of second behind ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]''.<ref name=BOMClueless>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=clueless.htm|title=Clueless (1995) - Box Office Mojo|work=boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> The film grossed $56,631,572 during its theatrical run, becoming the 32nd-highest-grossing film of 1995. This box office success brought the then-largely unknown Silverstone to international attention. The film also developed a strong [[cult following]] after its release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/07/05/an-oral-history-of-the-cult-classic-that-is-clueless/|title=An oral history of the cult classic that is 'Clueless'|date=2015-07-05|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-09-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=clueless.htm|title=Clueless (1995) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/07/21/clueless-at-20-what-hollywood-should-learn-from-the-pop-culture-classic/#75265a6a336c|title='Clueless' At 20: What Hollywood Should Learn From The Pop Culture Classic|last=Mendelson|first=Scott|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Clueless#tab=box-office|title=Cluelss (1995)|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics|Critical response}} \nThe film was well received by critics. Review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives it a score of 79% based on reviews from 63 critics and judged it \"Certified Fresh\" with an average rating of 6.89/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"A funny and clever reshaping of ''Emma'', ''Clueless'' offers a soft satire that pokes as much fun at teen films as it does at the Beverly Hills glitterati.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clueless/ | title=Clueless | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | date=July 21, 1995 | accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 68 out of 100 rating based on 18 reviews, which indicates \"generally positive reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clueless | title=Clueless | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film was seen as a teen flick that had a strong influence on fashion trends and lingo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/a11462/conversation-with-clueless-costume-designer/|title=Exclusive: Clueless' Costume Designer On Creating a Fashion Phenom|last=Pieri|first=Kerry|date=2016-07-19|website=Harper's BAZAAR|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/17/423740582/in-clothes-and-language-clueless-offered-counterpoint-to-grunge-crowd|title=20 Years Ago, 'Clueless' Like Totally Changed '90s Fashion And Vernacular|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Fashion as a form of self-expression played an important role in the narrative and character development of the film, television series, and novels, which are topics examined by Alice Leppert.<ref>Hunting, Kyra. \u201cFuriously Franchised: \u2018Clueless\u2019, Convergence Culture, and the Female-\nFocused Franchise.\u201d Cinema Journal, vol. 53, no. 3, 2014, pp. 145\u2013151., https://www.jstor.org/stable/43653627/</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half out of four stars.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clueless-1995 | title=Clueless Movie Review & Film Summary (1995) | work=[[Roger Ebert]] | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' notes, \"Even if ''Clueless'' runs out of gas before it's over, most of it is as eye-catching and cheery as its star.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE7D6163AF93AA25754C0A963958260 | title=Movie Review - Clueless \u2013 Film Review \u2013 A Teen-Ager Who's Clear on Her Priorities | work=[[Janet Maslin]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film four stars, contrasting it to the more adult-oriented film about teenagers released around the same time, ''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'', stating, \"The materialism in ''Clueless'' is almost as scary as the hopelessness in ''Kids''.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/clueless-19950719 | title=Movie Review: Clueless | work=[[Peter Travers]] | publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn 2008, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' selected ''Clueless'' as one of the \"New Classics,\" a list of 100 released between 1983 and 2008;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207063,00.html |title= The New Classics: Movies |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |date= 2008-06-27 |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref> ''Clueless'' was ranked 42nd,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20207076_20207079_20206941_8,00.html |title= Clueless, Alicia Silverstone, ... &#124; 100 New Movie Classics: No. 50-26 |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref> and they named it the 19th-best comedy of the past 25 years.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20221235_7,00.html |title= Clueless, Alicia Silverstone, ... &#124; The Comedy 25: The Funniest Movies of the Past 25 Years |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[American Film Institute]] recognition: \n*[[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Laughs]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> \u2013 Nominated\n*[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]] \u2013 \"As if!\" Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes Nominees |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Faithfulness to the text ==\nThe movie is a loose adaptation of [[Jane Austen]]'s 19-century novel [[Emma (novel)|''Emma'']].\n\n=== Characters ===\n'''Cher Horowitz/Emma Woodhouse''' \u2013 The title character Cher is representative of the main character Emma Woodhouse: Spunky, carefree, entitled, perpetually single, and matchmaker extraordinaire, both Cher and Emma enjoy the satisfaction of helping those who are without love find a perfect match. This is first seen within the first fifteen minutes of the film when both she and Dionne pair their English teacher with the school's Debate teacher. However, this is more prominently reflected when Cher does everything in her power to pair her newest friend Tai. While both Emma and Cher mean well in their matchmaking attempts, neither of them realizes the depths of their actions nor their feelings towards Josh/Mr. Knightly until Tai/Harriet asks her to set her up with Josh/Mr. Knightley.\n\n'''Josh/Mr. Knightley''' \u2013 Cher's stepbrother, who she finds utterly repulsive. She states at the beginning of the movie that she has no positive feelings towards Josh in the slightest. The two bicker on a near constant basis. However, as the movie progresses, Josh is shown to be more caring and considerate towards Cher, becoming defensive towards her choices of men and life choices. It is not until the end of the movie it is revealed that Josh is in love with Cher and the two share a passionate kiss. \n\n'''Miss Geist/Miss Taylor/Mrs. Weston''' \u2013 Target of Cher's matchmaking.\n\n'''Tai/Harriet Smith''' \u2013 Tai, representative of the young, fair, and socially awkward Harriet Smith, is a newcomer to Bronson Alcott High School. Soon after, she is swept off her feet by both Cher and Dionne as they help her (unintentionally) become the most popular girl in school, much to Cher's jealousy. At the beginning of the film, Tai is attracted to Travis, a well-meaning, skateboard riding, pot smoker social recluse though is encouraged by Cher to strive for someone more socially well off, as Travis is not considered to be a socially acceptable partner. Following this advice, Tai then falls for Josh, much to even more of Cher's Jealousy.\n\n'''Mel Horowitz/Mr. Henry Woodhouse''' \u2013 Just as in the book, Mr. Horowitz is a well known and respected man within his circle of friends, though there is one major difference between both characters: while Mr. Horowitz is shown to have little to no care for his health, Mr. Woodhouse is considered to be a [[valetudinarian]]. Both characters are shown to love their daughter greatly while not always being so forward in their affection.\n\n'''Travis/Robert Martin''' \u2013 A stoner and a skater who falls for Tai by the end of the film; however, their attempts at courtship are derailed for a time by Cher's attempts to set Tai up with Elton. Travis is an underachiever, constantly late for class and often receiving poor grades.\n\n'''Elton Tascia/Philip Elton''' \u2013 Elton is a popular student whom Cher attempts to fix up with Tai. As is the case with the Elton from the book, he is not interested in Tai/Harriet and mistakenly believes that Cher/Emma is interested in him.\n\n'''Christian/Frank Churchill''' \u2013 The initially appealing love interest of Cher with whom she convinces herself she must be in love (just like the Frank Churchill character in the book). In the book, Churchill is not available to Emma because he is already engaged; in the film, Christian is not available to Cher because he is gay. Both characters engage in surface-level flirting with the heroine and make her consider her own feelings.\n\n==Home media==\n''Clueless'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] on December 19, 1995 by [[Paramount Home Video]]. It was released on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on October 19, 1999. The special features only included two [[Trailer (promotion)|theatrical trailers]].\n\nThe film was reissued in a special tenth-anniversary \"''Whatever!'' Edition\" DVD on August 30, 2005. The new issue included featurettes and cast interviews, including:''The Class of '95'' (a look at the cast), ''Creative Writing'' (Amy Heckerling talks about the script), ''Fashion 101'' (how filmmakers invented the trendsetting style of ''Clueless''), ''Language Arts'' (the director and cast members give facts on the groundbreaking slang and how ''Clueless'' revived [[Valspeak]] slang), ''Suck and Blow'' (how to play the game depicted in the [[Sun Valley, Los Angeles|Sun Valley]] party scene), ''Driver's Ed'', ''We're History'' (stories from cast and crew of ''Clueless''), and two theatrical trailers.\n\nIt was released on [[Blu-ray]] on May 1, 2012. Special features were carried over from the \"''Whatever!'' Edition\" of 2005 and included a new trivia track.\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Track listing\n| title1          = [[Kids in America]]\n| note1           = [[The Muffs]]\n| length1         = 3:24\n\n| title2          = [[Shake Some Action]]\n| note2           = [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]\n| length2         = 4:25\n\n| title3          = [[The Ghost in You]]\n| note3           = [[Counting Crows]]\n| length3         = 3:30\n\n| title4          = [[Natural Ingredients|Here]] (Squirmel Mix)\n| note4           = [[Luscious Jackson]]\n| length4         = 3:33\n\n| title5          = [[All the Young Dudes (song)|All the Young Dudes]]\n| note5           = [[World Party]]\n| length5         = 4:00\n\n| title6          = [[Fake Plastic Trees]] (acoustic version)\n| note6           = [[Radiohead]]\n| length6         = 4:45\n\n| title7          = [[Jollification|Change]]\n| note7           = [[Lightning Seeds]]\n| length7         = 4:01\n\n| title8          = [[Need You Around]]\n| note8           = [[Smoking Popes]]\n| length8         = 3:42\n\n| title9          = [[Pretzel Nugget|Mullet Head]]\n| note9           = [[Beastie Boys]]\n| length9         = 2:53\n\n| title10         = [[Where'd You Go? (EP)|Where'd You Go?]]\n| note10          = [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]]\n| length10        = 3:16\n\n| title11         = Rollin' with My Homies\n| note11          = [[Coolio]]\n| length11        = 4:06\n\n| title12         = [[Alright (Supergrass song)|Alright]]\n| note12          = [[Supergrass]]\n| length12        = 3:01\n\n| title13         = [[Velocity Girl (album)|My Forgotten Favorite]]\n| note13          = [[Velocity Girl]]\n| length13        = 3:49\n\n| title14         = [[Jill Sobule (album)|Supermodel]]\n| note14          = [[Jill Sobule]]\n| length14        = 3:07\n\n}}\n\n==Cultural impact and legacy==\n===Cast===\n[[File:Brittany Murphy.jpg|thumb|150px|Brittany Murphy]]\nAfter the death of [[Brittany Murphy]], Silverstone stated that she \"always felt connected to [Murphy] as [they] shared a very special experience in [their] lives together.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine|date=December 20, 2009|title=Alicia Silverstone: I Hope Brittany Murphy Is at Peace|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20332103,00.html|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=2009-12-20}}</ref> Following Murphy's death, Silverstone reported in an interview: \"I loved working with Brittany. She was so talented, so warm, and so sweet.\"<ref name=\"people\"/>\n\nHeckerling later described Silverstone as having \"that [[Marilyn Monroe]] thing\" as a \"pretty, sweet blonde who, in spite of being the American ideal, people still really like.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bullettmedia.com/article/alicia-silverstone-is-forever-young/|title=Alicia Silverstone & Amy Heckerling: A Reunion|last=Haramis|first=Nick|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe surviving cast reunited in 2012 for an issue of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/04/clueless-reunion-entertainment-weekly-cher-dionne_n_1939925.html|title='Clueless' Reunion On Entertainment Weekly Makes Us Miss Cher And Dionne |work=The Huffington Post|date=October 5, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHeckerling later reunited with both Silverstone and Shawn for the vampire comedy ''[[Vamps (film)|Vamps]]''.\n\n===Popular culture and society===\nThe film was well known for the characters' catchphrases and vocabulary. Cher's verbal style is also marked by ironic contrasts between current slang and historical references, such as when she compares Tai to \"those Botticelli chicks\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=O'Meara |first=Jennifer |title='We've Got to Work on Your Accent and Vocabulary': Characterization through Verbal Style in 'Clueless.' |journal=[[Cinema Journal]] |volume=53 |issue=3 |year=2014 |pages=138\u2013145 |issn=0009-7101|jstor=43653626 |doi=10.1353/cj.2014.0031 }}</ref>\n\n''Clueless'' was the main inspiration for Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]]'s music video for her 2014 song \"[[Fancy (Iggy Azalea song)|Fancy]]\" featuring [[Charli XCX]]. Many visuals and costumes inspired by the film were used in the video,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1723476/iggy-azalea-fancy-charlie-xcx-clueless.jhtml|title=Iggy Azalea's 'Fancy' Video Is Basically An Exact Replica Of 'Clueless'|work=MTV News|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> which is filled with remakes of ''Clueless'' scenes. The outfits are also reinvented to channel the famous stylings of the film with a slightly modern edge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pepsi.com/en-us/d/content/2148/The-Stylist-for-Iggy-Azalea%E2%80%99s-Clueless-Themed-%E2%80%9CFancy%E2%80%9D-Music-Video-featuring-Charli-XCX-Tells-All |title=The Stylist for Iggy Azalea's Clueless-Themed \"Fancy\" Music Video featuring Charli XCX Tells All |publisher=Pepsi.com |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2014-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315174250/http://www.pepsi.com/en-us/d/content/2148/The-Stylist-for-Iggy-Azalea%E2%80%99s-Clueless-Themed-%E2%80%9CFancy%E2%80%9D-Music-Video-featuring-Charli-XCX-Tells-All |archive-date=March 15, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Fancy\" was shot in the same Los Angeles high school where ''Clueless'' was filmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com/news/culture/iggy-azaleas-new-video-copies-clueless |title=Iggy Azalea's New Video Copies 'Clueless' |work=Elle |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the second episode of the second season of the [[BBC America]] thriller series ''[[Killing Eve]]'', \"Nice and Neat\" (2019), the Russian assassin [[Villanelle (character)|Villanelle]] calls her agency and uses the codename Cher Horowitz to secretly inform her boss that she is in trouble and needs to be rescued after being kidnapped.\n\n==Spin-offs and adaptations==\n===Television===\nIn 1996, the producers created a [[Clueless (TV series)|spin-off television series]], which followed the continuing adventures of Cher and her friends. Several cast members from the film went on to star in the series, with the notable exceptions of Silverstone (who went on to sign a film deal with [[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]]-[[TriStar Pictures|TriStar]] worth $10 million) and Rudd (whose film career began to take off). Silverstone was replaced in the series with actress [[Rachel Blanchard]].\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that CBS would be adapting the film into a drama series. The series will be centered around Dionne after Cher goes missing, and is described by ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' as a \"baby pink and bisexual blue-tinted, tiny sunglasses-wearing, oat milk latte and Adderall-fueled look at what happens when the high school queen bee Cher disappears and her lifelong number two Dionne steps into Cher's vacant Air Jordans.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/film-tv/article/46468/1/the-clueless-reboot-will-focus-on-dionne-cbs-tv-studios|title=The Clueless reboot will focus on Dionne|last=Dawson|first=Brit|date=2019-10-18|website=[[Dazed]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n{{See also|Clueless (novels)}}\n[[Simon Spotlight Entertainment]] spun off a collection of paperback books, from 1995 to 1999, aimed at adolescent readers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://series.simonandschuster.net/Clueless/books |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724063536/http://series.simonandschuster.net/Clueless/books |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, to celebrate the film's twentieth anniversary, pop culture writer Jen Chaney published a book titled ''As If!: The Oral History of Clueless''. The book is based on exclusive interviews with Amy Heckerling, Alicia Silverstone, and other cast and crew members. Excerpts from the book were published in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simonandschusterpublishing.com/as-if/index.html|title=As If!|author=Jen Chaney|work=simonandschusterpublishing.com|accessdate=18 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203202713/http://www.simonandschusterpublishing.com/as-if/index.html|archive-date=February 3, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/clueless-oral-history-20-anniversary|title=An Oral History of Clueless - Vanity Fair|author=Jen Chaney|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\nA [[comic book]] series was launched in 2017.<ref>https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/11/boom-reveals-a-new-preview-of-clueless-one-last-su.html</ref>\n\n===Stage musical===\n''[[Clueless (musical)|Clueless: The Musical]]'' opened in [[New York City]] on December 11, 2018, as part of [[The New Group]]'s 2018\u20132019 season. The show was written by Heckerling and starred [[Dove Cameron]] as Cher and Dave Thomas Brown as Josh. It closed on January 12, 2019 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/clueless-musical-starring-dove-cameron-begins-previews-november-20|title=Clueless Musical, Starring Dove Cameron, Begins Previews November 20|work=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]|last=Gans|first=Andrew|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe musical was a [[jukebox musical]] featuring [[1990s in music|pop songs from the 1990s]], though with lyrics mostly or entirely rewritten by Heckerling to fit the storyline. Songs adapted from the movie's soundtrack included \"[[Jill Sobule (album)|Supermodel]]\" and \"[[Kids in America]].\"\n\n===Web story===\nIn 2017, [[Episode (app)|Episode]] launched an animated web story based on the film.<ref>https://venturebeat.com/2017/08/16/pocket-gems-episode-brings-back-clueless-as-an-interactive-mobile-game/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Novels|Literature|Los Angeles|Film|United States|1990s}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Cinema of the United States]]\n* [[Clueless (musical)]]\n* [[Clueless (novels)]]\n* [[Clueless (TV series)]]\n* [[Cult following]]\n* [[List of Clueless characters]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0112697|Clueless}}\n* {{AllMovie title|134935|Clueless}}\n* {{tcmdb title|71132|Clueless}}\n* {{AFI film|67154|Clueless}}\n* {{mojo title|clueless|Clueless}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|clueless|Clueless}}\n* {{metacritic film|clueless|Clueless}}\n\n{{clueless}}\n{{Emma}}\n{{Amy Heckerling}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clueless}}\n[[Category:1990s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s female buddy films]]\n[[Category:1990s high school films]]\n[[Category:1990s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American female buddy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American teen romance films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films about virginity]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Films based on Emma (novel)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Amy Heckerling]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Scott Rudin]]\n[[Category:Films set in Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Amy Heckerling]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related comedy films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1995 film by Amy Heckerling}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Clueless\n| image          = Clueless film poster.png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Amy Heckerling]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Scott Rudin]]\n* [[Robert Lawrence (producer)|Robert Lawrence]]\n}}\n| writer         = Amy Heckerling\n| based on       = <!-- Do not add Emma here, was not a credited adaptation -->\n| starring       = [[Alicia Silverstone]]<!--Only Silverstone's name appears on the poster-->\n| music          = [[David Kitay]]\n| cinematography = [[Bill Pope]]\n| editing        = Debra Chiate\n| studio         = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1995|7|19|United States}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 97:24--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/clueless-1970-1 | title=''Clueless'' (12) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=July 28, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $12 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://powergrid.thewrap.com/project/clueless|title=Clueless - PowerGrid|work=thewrap.com|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $56.6 million<ref name=BOMClueless/>\n}}\n'''''Clueless''''' is a 1995 American [[Coming-of-age story|coming-of-age]] [[Teen film|teen]] [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[Amy Heckerling]]. It stars [[Alicia Silverstone]], [[Stacey Dash]], [[Paul Rudd]], [[Dan Hedaya]], and [[Brittany Murphy]]. It was produced by [[Scott Rudin]] and [[Robert Lawrence (producer)|Robert Lawrence]]. It is loosely based on [[Jane Austen]]'s 1815 novel ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'', with a modern-day setting of [[Beverly Hills]].<ref>[http://www.jasna.org/persuasions/on-line/opno3/mazmanian.html Mazmanian, Melissa. \"Reviving ''Emma'' in a ''Clueless'' World: The Current Attraction to a Classic Structure.] Persuasions Online: Occasional Papers No. 3. Fall 1999. Jane Austen Society of North America website. Accessed November 12, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.australianhumanitiesreview.org/archive/Issue-August-1997/stern.html Stern, Lesley. \"Emma in Los Angeles\" ''Clueless'' as a remake of the book and the city.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006181505/http://www.australianhumanitiesreview.org/archive/Issue-August-1997/stern.html |date=October 6, 2013 }} Australian Humanities Review website, 1997. Accessed November 12, 2013.</ref> The plot centers on Cher Horowitz, a rich and beautiful high school student who befriends a new student named Tai Frasier and decides to give her a makeover.\n\n''Clueless'' was filmed in California over a 40-day schedule. The film's director studied real Beverly Hills high school students to learn the lingo and to understand how real teens in the 1990s talked.\n\nThe film grossed $56.1 million in the United States. It has received generally positive reviews from critics and is considered to be one of the [[List of films considered the best|best teen films of all time]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Clueless {{!}} Issue 109 {{!}} Philosophy Now|url = https://philosophynow.org/issues/109/Clueless|website = philosophynow.org|accessdate = 2015-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/07/05/an-oral-history-of-the-cult-classic-that-is-clueless/ |title=An oral history of the cult classic that is 'Clueless' |newspaper=New York Post |date=July 5, 2015 |author=Susannah Cahalan |accessdate=July 12, 2015|author-link=Susannah Cahalan }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chacha.com/gallery/3438/which-90s-films-are-cult-classics/33173 |title=Which 90s Films Are Cult Classics? |publisher=ChaCha |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713122440/http://www.chacha.com/gallery/3438/which-90s-films-are-cult-classics/33173 |archive-date=July 13, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.neontommy.com/news/2014/07/5-cult-classic-films-never-get-old |title=5 Cult Classic Films That Never Get Old |work=Neon Tommy |date=July 21, 2014 |first=Ashley |last=Hawkins |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223080017/http://www.neontommy.com/news/2014/07/5-cult-classic-films-never-get-old |archive-date=February 23, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Clueless'' has developed a [[cult following]] and has a continuing legacy. The film was followed by a spin-off [[Clueless (TV series)|television sitcom]], [[Clueless (novels)|series of books]], and Paramount Studios has announced that they are producing a remake.\n\n==Plot==\nCher Horowitz lives in a Beverly Hills mansion with her father Mel, a $500-an-hour [[litigator]]; her mother died during a routine [[liposuction]] procedure when Cher was a baby. Cher is attractive, popular, and wealthy. She attends Bronson Alcott High School with her best friend, Dionne Davenport, who is also wealthy and beautiful. Dionne has a long-term relationship with popular student Murray; Cher claims that this is a pointless endeavor for Dionne.\n\nJosh, Cher's socially conscious ex-stepbrother, visits her during a break from college. They spar continually but playfully. She mocks his idealism, while he teases her for being selfish, vain and superficial, saying that her only direction in life is \"toward the mall\". Cher plays matchmaker for two hard-grading teachers at her school, Mr. Hall and Miss Geist. She facilitates the relationship between the teachers to make them relax their grading standards so she can renegotiate a bad grade on her report card. After she sees their newfound happiness, she realizes she enjoys doing good deeds. She then decides to give back to the community by \"adopting\" a \"tragically [[Hip (slang)|unhip]]\" new girl at school, Tai Frasier. Cher and Dionne give Tai a makeover, which gives Tai confidence and a sense of style. Cher also tries to extinguish the attraction between Tai and Travis Birkenstock, an amiable skateboarding slacker, and to steer her towards Elton, a popular and wealthy student.\n\nElton rejects Tai and fails to seduce Cher. A handsome new student at their school named Christian becomes Cher's target boyfriend. Murray explains to Cher and Dionne that Christian is gay. Despite the failure of this endeavor, Cher remains on friendly terms with Christian, primarily due to her admiration of his taste in art and fashion. Matters take a turn for the worse when Tai's newfound popularity strains her relationship with Cher. Cher's frustration escalates when she fails her driving test and cannot change the result. When she returns home, crushed, Tai confesses her feelings for Josh and wants Cher's help in pursuing him. Cher says Tai is not right for Josh and they quarrel. Their disagreement ends with Tai calling Cher a \"virgin who can't drive\". Feeling \"totally clueless\", Cher reflects on her priorities and her repeated failures to understand or appreciate the people in her life.\n\nAfter thinking about why she is bothered by Tai's interest in Josh, Cher realizes that she loves him. She begins making awkward but sincere efforts to live a more purposeful life, including captaining the school's [[Pismo Beach]] disaster relief effort. Cher and Josh eventually admit their feelings for one another, culminating in a tender kiss. Ultimately, Mr. Hall and Miss Geist wed; Cher's friendships with Tai and Dionne are solidified; Tai and Travis are in love and Cher catches the wedding bouquet, helping Josh win a $200 bet. She embraces Josh and they kiss.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Anchor|Cast}}\n{{See also|List of Clueless characters}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Alicia Silverstone]] as Cher Horowitz\n* [[Stacey Dash]] as Dionne Davenport\n* [[Brittany Murphy]] as Tai Frasier\n* [[Paul Rudd]] as Josh Lucas\n* [[Dan Hedaya]] as Melvin \"Mel\" Horowitz (\"Hamilton\" in the credits)\n* [[Elisa Donovan]] as Amber Mariens\n* [[Justin Walker (actor)|Justin Walker]] as Christian Stovitz\n*[[Wallace Shawn]] as Mr. Wendell Hall\n*[[Twink Caplan]] as Ms. Toby Geist\n*[[Julie Brown]] as Coach Millie Stoeger\n*[[Donald Faison]] as Murray Duvall, Dionne's long-term boyfriend\n*[[Breckin Meyer]] as Travis Birkenstock\n*[[Jeremy Sisto]] as Elton Tiscia\n*[[Nicole Bilderback]] as Summer Han\n*Sean Holland as Lawrence\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAccording to the special feature titled \"''Creative Writing''\", Heckerling describes the origins of ''Clueless'' as follows:\n{{quote|I went to [[20th Century Fox]] and they said \"We want you to do something about teenagers.\" And I thought \"I'm so tired about doing stuff about teenagers.\" But they said, \"We want you to do something about the 'in' crowd.\" I thought \"I'll do it if I can make fun of them.\" So, we developed this script. It was a pilot for a TV show. And it was about this girl that was completely happy, no matter what happened. And I was really getting into that kind of character. But nothing happened with it. They passed on it, they didn't get it. And a number of things were sort of falling through. I was just getting very frustrated. So I switched agents and when I had my new agent, they said: \"What have you been working on?\" So I showed Ken Stovitz, one of the agents there, this pilot. And he said, \"This is too good for TV. You should make this into a feature.\"<ref name=\"Creative\">{{cite news|url=https://vimeo.com/343465997|title=''Clueless'' - Creative Writing|publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>}}\n\nShe follows up on the connections to the [[Jane Austen]] novel, ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'':\n{{quote|I started to think, \"What's the larger context for that kind of a 'nothing can go wrong' 'always looks through rose colored glasses' kind of girl?\" And I remembered ''Emma'', which I'd read in college. So, I took it out and reread it, and I said: \"Unconsciously, I've been writing an Emma-like character.\" Because I've always loved it and part of it had sort of stored it away in my brain... So I really related to her and got into it. And the plot was so brilliantly laid out in ''Emma''. So I tried to take all the things that were in this sort of pretty 1800s world and see what would that be like if it was in [[Beverly Hills]].<ref name=\"Creative\" />}} \n\nAssociate producer [[Twink Caplan]] recalls what the proposed TV show's initial title:\n{{quote|''No Worries'' was the original television script that Amy wrote. Then, we went to ''I Was a Teenage Teenager'' because with every new draft that Amy writes, she picks a whole new title.<ref name=\"Creative\" />}}\n\nFox picked up the picture, but put the film in a [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]]. The male studio heads wanted Heckerling to rewrite the script so that fewer women would feature. Six months later, the script made its way to producer [[Scott Rudin]]. Rudin like the script and it was the subject of a bidding war, with [[Paramount Pictures]] beating out the other studios. Heckerling was excited, as Paramount owned several major youth-centered channels, such as [[MTV]] and [[Nickelodeon]], which was suited to the film's target demographic.<ref name=\"Creative\" />\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Westfield Fashion Square.JPG|Westfield Fashion Square|thumb|150px|The Westfield Fashion Square]]\nPrincipal photography for the film took place between November 21 and December 31, 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Alicia Silverstone Stars in 'Clueless,' A Romantic Comedy Written and Directed by Amy Heckelilng|url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ALICIA+SILVERSTONE+STARS+IN+'CLUELESS,'+A+ROMANTIC+COMEDY+WRITTEN+AND...-a015982332|website = thefreelibrary.com|access-date = 2016-02-05}}</ref> The film had a 40-day filming schedule. Producers sat in on classes at [[Beverly Hills High School]] to get a feel for the student culture. Herb Hall, the real drama teacher at Beverly Hills High School, had a short scene as the principal in the film. Scenes depicting the high school campus, including the tennis courts, the outdoor cafeteria, the quad, and various classrooms were filmed at [[Occidental College]] in [[Los Angeles]]. The mall scenes were filmed at [[Westfield Fashion Square]] in [[Sherman Oaks, California]].\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{Anchor|Box office}}\nThe film became a surprise [[sleeper hit]] of 1995. ''Clueless'' opened in 1,653 theaters on July 19, 1995 and grossed $10,612,443 on its opening weekend, which led to a ranking of second behind ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]''.<ref name=BOMClueless>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=clueless.htm|title=Clueless (1995) - Box Office Mojo|work=boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> The film grossed $56,631,572 during its theatrical run, becoming the 32nd-highest-grossing film of 1995. This box office success brought the then-largely unknown Silverstone to international attention. The film also developed a strong [[cult following]] after its release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/07/05/an-oral-history-of-the-cult-classic-that-is-clueless/|title=An oral history of the cult classic that is 'Clueless'|date=2015-07-05|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-09-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=clueless.htm|title=Clueless (1995) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/07/21/clueless-at-20-what-hollywood-should-learn-from-the-pop-culture-classic/#75265a6a336c|title='Clueless' At 20: What Hollywood Should Learn From The Pop Culture Classic|last=Mendelson|first=Scott|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Clueless#tab=box-office|title=Cluelss (1995)|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Anchor|Critics|Critical response}} \nThe film was well received by critics. Review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives it a score of 79% based on reviews from 63 critics and judged it \"Certified Fresh\" with an average rating of 6.89/10. The site's critical consensus reads: \"A funny and clever reshaping of ''Emma'', ''Clueless'' offers a soft satire that pokes as much fun at teen films as it does at the Beverly Hills glitterati.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/clueless/ | title=Clueless | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | date=July 21, 1995 | accessdate=July 10, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a 68 out of 100 rating based on 18 reviews, which indicates \"generally positive reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/clueless | title=Clueless | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film was seen as a teen flick that had a strong influence on fashion trends and lingo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/film-tv/a11462/conversation-with-clueless-costume-designer/|title=Exclusive: Clueless' Costume Designer On Creating a Fashion Phenom|last=Pieri|first=Kerry|date=2016-07-19|website=Harper's BAZAAR|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/07/17/423740582/in-clothes-and-language-clueless-offered-counterpoint-to-grunge-crowd|title=20 Years Ago, 'Clueless' Like Totally Changed '90s Fashion And Vernacular|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> Fashion as a form of self-expression played an important role in the narrative and character development of the film, television series, and novels, which are topics examined by Alice Leppert.<ref>Hunting, Kyra. \u201cFuriously Franchised: \u2018Clueless\u2019, Convergence Culture, and the Female-\nFocused Franchise.\u201d Cinema Journal, vol. 53, no. 3, 2014, pp. 145\u2013151., https://www.jstor.org/stable/43653627/</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three-and-a-half out of four stars.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/clueless-1995 | title=Clueless Movie Review & Film Summary (1995) | work=[[Roger Ebert]] | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' notes, \"Even if ''Clueless'' runs out of gas before it's over, most of it is as eye-catching and cheery as its star.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE7D6163AF93AA25754C0A963958260 | title=Movie Review - Clueless \u2013 Film Review \u2013 A Teen-Ager Who's Clear on Her Priorities | work=[[Janet Maslin]] | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film four stars, contrasting it to the more adult-oriented film about teenagers released around the same time, ''[[Kids (film)|Kids]]'', stating, \"The materialism in ''Clueless'' is almost as scary as the hopelessness in ''Kids''.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/clueless-19950719 | title=Movie Review: Clueless | work=[[Peter Travers]] | publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=July 19, 1995 | accessdate=July 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn 2008, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' selected ''Clueless'' as one of the \"New Classics,\" a list of 100 released between 1983 and 2008;<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207063,00.html |title= The New Classics: Movies |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |date= 2008-06-27 |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref> ''Clueless'' was ranked 42nd,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20207076_20207079_20206941_8,00.html |title= Clueless, Alicia Silverstone, ... &#124; 100 New Movie Classics: No. 50-26 |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref> and they named it the 19th-best comedy of the past 25 years.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20221235_7,00.html |title= Clueless, Alicia Silverstone, ... &#124; The Comedy 25: The Funniest Movies of the Past 25 Years |publisher= Time | work = Entertainment Weekly |accessdate= 2009-07-03}}</ref>\n\n[[American Film Institute]] recognition: \n*[[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Laughs]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs500.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Laughs Nominees |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> \u2013 Nominated\n*[[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes]] \u2013 \"As if!\" Nominated<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/quotes400.pdf |title=AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes Nominees |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Faithfulness to the text ==\nThe movie is a loose adaptation of [[Jane Austen]]'s 19-century novel [[Emma (novel)|''Emma'']].\n\n=== Characters ===\n'''Cher Horowitz/Emma Woodhouse''' \u2013 The title character Cher is representative of the main character Emma Woodhouse: Spunky, carefree, entitled, perpetually single, and matchmaker extraordinaire, both Cher and Emma enjoy the satisfaction of helping those who are without love find a perfect match. This is first seen within the first fifteen minutes of the film when both she and Dionne pair their English teacher with the school's Debate teacher. However, this is more prominently reflected when Cher does everything in her power to pair her newest friend Tai. While both Emma and Cher mean well in their matchmaking attempts, neither of them realizes the depths of their actions nor their feelings towards Josh/Mr. Knightly until Tai/Harriet asks her to set her up with Josh/Mr. Knightley.\n\n'''Josh/Mr. Knightley''' \u2013 Cher's stepbrother, who she finds utterly repulsive. She states at the beginning of the movie that she has no positive feelings towards Josh in the slightest. The two bicker on a near constant basis. However, as the movie progresses, Josh is shown to be more caring and considerate towards Cher, becoming defensive towards her choices of men and life choices. It is not until the end of the movie it is revealed that Josh is in love with Cher and the two share a passionate kiss. \n\n'''Miss Geist/Miss Taylor/Mrs. Weston''' \u2013 Target of Cher's matchmaking.\n\n'''Tai/Harriet Smith''' \u2013 Tai, representative of the young, fair, and socially awkward Harriet Smith, is a newcomer to Bronson Alcott High School. Soon after, she is swept off her feet by both Cher and Dionne as they help her (unintentionally) become the most popular girl in school, much to Cher's jealousy. At the beginning of the film, Tai is attracted to Travis, a well-meaning, skateboard riding, pot smoker social recluse though is encouraged by Cher to strive for someone more socially well off, as Travis is not considered to be a socially acceptable partner. Following this advice, Tai then falls for Josh, much to even more of Cher's Jealousy.\n\n'''Mel Horowitz/Mr. Henry Woodhouse''' \u2013 Just as in the book, Mr. Horowitz is a well known and respected man within his circle of friends, though there is one major difference between both characters: while Mr. Horowitz is shown to have little to no care for his health, Mr. Woodhouse is considered to be a [[valetudinarian]]. Both characters are shown to love their daughter greatly while not always being so forward in their affection.\n\n'''Travis/Robert Martin''' \u2013 A stoner and a skater who falls for Tai by the end of the film; however, their attempts at courtship are derailed for a time by Cher's attempts to set Tai up with Elton. Travis is an underachiever, constantly late for class and often receiving poor grades.\n\n'''Elton Tascia/Philip Elton''' \u2013 Elton is a popular student whom Cher attempts to fix up with Tai. As is the case with the Elton from the book, he is not interested in Tai/Harriet and mistakenly believes that Cher/Emma is interested in him.\n\n'''Christian/Frank Churchill''' \u2013 The initially appealing love interest of Cher with whom she convinces herself she must be in love (just like the Frank Churchill character in the book). In the book, Churchill is not available to Emma because he is already engaged; in the film, Christian is not available to Cher because he is gay. Both characters engage in surface-level flirting with the heroine and make her consider her own feelings.\n\n==Home media==\n''Clueless'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] on December 19, 1995 by [[Paramount Home Video]]. It was released on [[DVD-Video|DVD]] on October 19, 1999. The special features only included two [[Trailer (promotion)|theatrical trailers]].\n\nThe film was reissued in a special tenth-anniversary \"''Whatever!'' Edition\" DVD on August 30, 2005. The new issue included featurettes and cast interviews, including:''The Class of '95'' (a look at the cast), ''Creative Writing'' (Amy Heckerling talks about the script), ''Fashion 101'' (how filmmakers invented the trendsetting style of ''Clueless''), ''Language Arts'' (the director and cast members give facts on the groundbreaking slang and how ''Clueless'' revived [[Valspeak]] slang), ''Suck and Blow'' (how to play the game depicted in the [[Sun Valley, Los Angeles|Sun Valley]] party scene), ''Driver's Ed'', ''We're History'' (stories from cast and crew of ''Clueless''), and two theatrical trailers.\n\nIt was released on [[Blu-ray]] on May 1, 2012. Special features were carried over from the \"''Whatever!'' Edition\" of 2005 and included a new trivia track.\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = Track listing\n| title1          = [[Kids in America]]\n| note1           = [[The Muffs]]\n| length1         = 3:24\n\n| title2          = [[Shake Some Action]]\n| note2           = [[Cracker (band)|Cracker]]\n| length2         = 4:25\n\n| title3          = [[The Ghost in You]]\n| note3           = [[Counting Crows]]\n| length3         = 3:30\n\n| title4          = [[Natural Ingredients|Here]] (Squirmel Mix)\n| note4           = [[Luscious Jackson]]\n| length4         = 3:33\n\n| title5          = [[All the Young Dudes (song)|All the Young Dudes]]\n| note5           = [[World Party]]\n| length5         = 4:00\n\n| title6          = [[Fake Plastic Trees]] (acoustic version)\n| note6           = [[Radiohead]]\n| length6         = 4:45\n\n| title7          = [[Jollification|Change]]\n| note7           = [[Lightning Seeds]]\n| length7         = 4:01\n\n| title8          = [[Need You Around]]\n| note8           = [[Smoking Popes]]\n| length8         = 3:42\n\n| title9          = [[Pretzel Nugget|Mullet Head]]\n| note9           = [[Beastie Boys]]\n| length9         = 2:53\n\n| title10         = [[Where'd You Go? (EP)|Where'd You Go?]]\n| note10          = [[The Mighty Mighty Bosstones]]\n| length10        = 3:16\n\n| title11         = Rollin' with My Homies\n| note11          = [[Coolio]]\n| length11        = 4:06\n\n| title12         = [[Alright (Supergrass song)|Alright]]\n| note12          = [[Supergrass]]\n| length12        = 3:01\n\n| title13         = [[Velocity Girl (album)|My Forgotten Favorite]]\n| note13          = [[Velocity Girl]]\n| length13        = 3:49\n\n| title14         = [[Jill Sobule (album)|Supermodel]]\n| note14          = [[Jill Sobule]]\n| length14        = 3:07\n\n}}\n\n==Cultural impact and legacy==\n===Cast===\n[[File:Brittany Murphy.jpg|thumb|150px|Brittany Murphy]]\nAfter the death of [[Brittany Murphy]], Silverstone stated that she \"always felt connected to [Murphy] as [they] shared a very special experience in [their] lives together.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine|date=December 20, 2009|title=Alicia Silverstone: I Hope Brittany Murphy Is at Peace|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20332103,00.html|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=2009-12-20}}</ref> Following Murphy's death, Silverstone reported in an interview: \"I loved working with Brittany. She was so talented, so warm, and so sweet.\"<ref name=\"people\"/>\n\nHeckerling later described Silverstone as having \"that [[Marilyn Monroe]] thing\" as a \"pretty, sweet blonde who, in spite of being the American ideal, people still really like.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bullettmedia.com/article/alicia-silverstone-is-forever-young/|title=Alicia Silverstone & Amy Heckerling: A Reunion|last=Haramis|first=Nick|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe surviving cast reunited in 2012 for an issue of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/04/clueless-reunion-entertainment-weekly-cher-dionne_n_1939925.html|title='Clueless' Reunion On Entertainment Weekly Makes Us Miss Cher And Dionne |work=The Huffington Post|date=October 5, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHeckerling later reunited with both Silverstone and Shawn for the vampire comedy ''[[Vamps (film)|Vamps]]''.\n\n===Popular culture and society===\nThe film was well known for the characters' catchphrases and vocabulary. Cher's verbal style is also marked by ironic contrasts between current slang and historical references, such as when she compares Tai to \"those Botticelli chicks\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=O'Meara |first=Jennifer |title='We've Got to Work on Your Accent and Vocabulary': Characterization through Verbal Style in 'Clueless.' |journal=[[Cinema Journal]] |volume=53 |issue=3 |year=2014 |pages=138\u2013145 |issn=0009-7101|jstor=43653626 |doi=10.1353/cj.2014.0031 }}</ref>\n\n''Clueless'' was the main inspiration for Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]]'s music video for her 2014 song \"[[Fancy (Iggy Azalea song)|Fancy]]\" featuring [[Charli XCX]]. Many visuals and costumes inspired by the film were used in the video,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1723476/iggy-azalea-fancy-charlie-xcx-clueless.jhtml|title=Iggy Azalea's 'Fancy' Video Is Basically An Exact Replica Of 'Clueless'|work=MTV News|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> which is filled with remakes of ''Clueless'' scenes. The outfits are also reinvented to channel the famous stylings of the film with a slightly modern edge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pepsi.com/en-us/d/content/2148/The-Stylist-for-Iggy-Azalea%E2%80%99s-Clueless-Themed-%E2%80%9CFancy%E2%80%9D-Music-Video-featuring-Charli-XCX-Tells-All |title=The Stylist for Iggy Azalea's Clueless-Themed \"Fancy\" Music Video featuring Charli XCX Tells All |publisher=Pepsi.com |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2014-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315174250/http://www.pepsi.com/en-us/d/content/2148/The-Stylist-for-Iggy-Azalea%E2%80%99s-Clueless-Themed-%E2%80%9CFancy%E2%80%9D-Music-Video-featuring-Charli-XCX-Tells-All |archive-date=March 15, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \"Fancy\" was shot in the same Los Angeles high school where ''Clueless'' was filmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com/news/culture/iggy-azaleas-new-video-copies-clueless |title=Iggy Azalea's New Video Copies 'Clueless' |work=Elle |date=2014-03-04 |accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the second episode of the second season of the [[BBC America]] thriller series ''[[Killing Eve]]'', \"Nice and Neat\" (2019), the Russian assassin [[Villanelle (character)|Villanelle]] calls her agency and uses the codename Cher Horowitz to secretly inform her boss that she is in trouble and needs to be rescued after being kidnapped.\n\n==Spin-offs and adaptations==\n===Television===\nIn 1996, the producers created a [[Clueless (TV series)|spin-off television series]], which followed the continuing adventures of Cher and her friends. Several cast members from the film went on to star in the series, with the notable exceptions of Silverstone (who went on to sign a film deal with [[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]]-[[TriStar Pictures|TriStar]] worth $10 million) and Rudd (whose film career began to take off). Silverstone was replaced in the series with actress [[Rachel Blanchard]].\n\nIn October 2019, it was announced that CBS would be adapting the film into a drama series. The series will be centered around Dionne after Cher goes missing, and is described by ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' as a \"baby pink and bisexual blue-tinted, tiny sunglasses-wearing, oat milk latte and Adderall-fueled look at what happens when the high school queen bee Cher disappears and her lifelong number two Dionne steps into Cher's vacant Air Jordans.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/film-tv/article/46468/1/the-clueless-reboot-will-focus-on-dionne-cbs-tv-studios|title=The Clueless reboot will focus on Dionne|last=Dawson|first=Brit|date=2019-10-18|website=[[Dazed]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n{{See also|Clueless (novels)}}\n[[Simon Spotlight Entertainment]] spun off a collection of paperback books, from 1995 to 1999, aimed at adolescent readers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://series.simonandschuster.net/Clueless/books |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724063536/http://series.simonandschuster.net/Clueless/books |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, to celebrate the film's twentieth anniversary, pop culture writer Jen Chaney published a book titled ''As If!: The Oral History of Clueless''. The book is based on exclusive interviews with Amy Heckerling, Alicia Silverstone, and other cast and crew members. Excerpts from the book were published in ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.simonandschusterpublishing.com/as-if/index.html|title=As If!|author=Jen Chaney|work=simonandschusterpublishing.com|accessdate=18 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180203202713/http://www.simonandschusterpublishing.com/as-if/index.html|archive-date=February 3, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/clueless-oral-history-20-anniversary|title=An Oral History of Clueless - Vanity Fair|author=Jen Chaney|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\nA [[comic book]] series was launched in 2017.<ref>https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/11/boom-reveals-a-new-preview-of-clueless-one-last-su.html</ref>\n\n===Stage musical===\n''[[Clueless (musical)|Clueless: The Musical]]'' opened in [[New York City]] on December 11, 2018, as part of [[The New Group]]'s 2018\u20132019 season. The show was written by Heckerling and starred [[Dove Cameron]] as Cher and Dave Thomas Brown as Josh. It closed on January 12, 2019 .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/clueless-musical-starring-dove-cameron-begins-previews-november-20|title=Clueless Musical, Starring Dove Cameron, Begins Previews November 20|work=[[Playbill (magazine)|Playbill]]|last=Gans|first=Andrew|accessdate=November 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe musical was a [[jukebox musical]] featuring [[1990s in music|pop songs from the 1990s]], though with lyrics mostly or entirely rewritten by Heckerling to fit the storyline. Songs adapted from the movie's soundtrack included \"[[Jill Sobule (album)|Supermodel]]\" and \"[[Kids in America]].\"\n\n===Web story===\nIn 2017, [[Episode (app)|Episode]] launched an animated web story based on the film.<ref>https://venturebeat.com/2017/08/16/pocket-gems-episode-brings-back-clueless-as-an-interactive-mobile-game/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Novels|Literature|Los Angeles|Film|United States|1990s}}\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Cinema of the United States]]\n* [[Clueless (musical)]]\n* [[Clueless (novels)]]\n* [[Clueless (TV series)]]\n* [[Cult following]]\n* [[List of Clueless characters]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0112697|Clueless}}\n* {{AllMovie title|134935|Clueless}}\n* {{tcmdb title|71132|Clueless}}\n* {{AFI film|67154|Clueless}}\n* {{mojo title|clueless|Clueless}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|clueless|Clueless}}\n* {{metacritic film|clueless|Clueless}}\n\n{{clueless}}\n{{Emma}}\n{{Amy Heckerling}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clueless}}\n[[Category:1990s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s female buddy films]]\n[[Category:1990s high school films]]\n[[Category:1990s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American buddy comedy films]]